the following are excerpts from the official vatican translation in english of pope john paul ii's easter sunday message, ``urbi et orbi'' (to the city and world), given in italian:
queen of heaven rejoice! behold, precisely today on this first day after the sabbath the women went to the tomb, where the body of your son had been laid, having been taken down from the cross, and they found the stone rolled away, and the tomb empty
from within the tomb they heard a voice: ``do not be amazed; you seek jesus of nazareth, who was crucified. he has risen, he is not here.''
rejoice, queen of heaven! rejoice, mother of chirst!
but go, tell his disciples and peter.''
then mary of magdala ran to tell the apostles: ``they have taken the lord out of the tomb, and we do not know where they haven laid him.''
peter and john went at once to the place, and they found that it was as the women had said. he is not here. he is not here, in the place where they laid him, in the tomb. he is not here _ he has risen
rejoice, queen of heaven!
rejoice, queen of heaven. ... what the tongues of the first witnesses now proclaim had first been foretold by himself
destroy this temple, and in three days i will raise it up .. . he spoke of the temple of his body.'' his scourged, tortured crucified body; his head wounded by the thorns; his side pierced by the lance. he is not here. ... rejoice, queen of heaven!
rejoice, mary, rejoice, mother!
you bore his body in your virginal womb, you bore within you the god-man. and then you brought him forth on the night of bethlehem, you bore him in your arms as a child. you bore him into the temple on the day of his presentation. your eyes _ more than the eyes of anyone else _ saw the incarnate word. your ears heard him, from his very first words. your hands touched the word of life. rejoice, queen of heaven! ``he whom you bore has risen.''
you bore him, even more than in your arms, in your heart. particularly during those last hours, when you had to stand beneath the cross, at the feet of the divine condemned one. your heart was pierced by the sword of sorrow, in accordance with the words of the aged simeon. and you shared the sorrow as you associated yourself, with your maternal soul, in the sacrifice of your son
o mother! you consented to the immolation of the victim whom you had borne. you lovingly consented _ with that love which is planted in your heart. with that love which is stronger than death and stronger than sin, in the whole history of man on earth
and then, when he had breathed his last, and they had taken him down from the cross, he rested once more in your arms, as he has rested so many times before as a child ... and then, they laid him in the tomb. they took him from your maternal arms and gave him back to the earth; they closed the tomb with a stone ... and behold, now the stone has been rolled away, the tomb is empty. christ whom you bore is risen, hallelujah! rejoice, queen of heaven! this is the day of the church's easter joy we all share in your glory, o mother ... everyone, the whole church of your son, the whole church of the incarnate word
christ whom you bore is risen! pray for us! your who were present in the deepest possible way in the mystery of christ. behold, the whole church today looks to you, o mary. even though we do not see you among the people about whom the accounts of easter tell, we all look to you. we look to your heart. could any narrative record the moment of the resurrection of the son in the heart of his mother? yet we fix our gaze on you. the whole church shares in your easter joy the whole church knows that on this day that the lord has made you ``go before'' in a singular way along this path of pilgrimage of faith in paschal mystery. pray for us!
during this year which has been dedicated in a particular way to you, during this marian year, be present in a special way in the church, be present along all the paths of the people of god, paths upon which shines the light of christ. let this light never leave anyone, this light of the new life which is he himself, the risen one! king speech; picks up 3rd graf, `on monday ...'; adds 2 grafs with portland march; note `promise land' in 4th graf quote is cq.</note>
the legacy of the rev. martin luther king jr., assassinated 20 years ago monday, was remembered around the country sunday by blacks and whites continuing the fight for racial equality and social justice that king began
twenty years later, everything has changed and nothing has changed,'' joseph lowery, president of the southern christian leadership conference, a civil rights organization formed by king, said sunday night at a memorial service in memphis, tenn
america's poor are as bad off as ever, speakers told the 500 people attending the service at the mason temple where king gave his ``mountain top'' speech on the eve of his murder at the lorraine motel in memphis
i've been to the mountain top ... i've looked over, and i've seen the promise land,'' king said in the speech. ``i may not get there with you, but i want you to know tonight, that we as a people will get to the promised land.''
benjamin hooks, president of the national association for the advancement of colored people, said the address was one of the most emotional he had heard king deliver
it was a tremendous experience,'' hooks said before speaking to about 500 people attending the memphis service
hooks urged the audience to renew its commitment to king's ``poor people's campaign,'' which was under way at the time of his death
so dr. king, we haven't made it yet ... but we are determined from this day, we are going to march forward, and ain't nobody going to turn us around,'' he said
on monday in memphis, a memorial sponsored by the city is to begin with a ceremony at the lorraine, followed by the beginning of a southern christian leadership conference march through alabama, mississippi and georgia. that march is to conclude april 30 in atlanta
a simple wreath-laying ceremony will be held monday afternoon at king's tomb in atlanta at the martin luther king jr. center for nonviolent social change
king's widow, coretta scott king, has long favored an approach focusing on her late husband's life, not his death. last year, she came out in opposition to plans to make the lorraine motel a museum, and said she did not want such a project to bear his name
also in atlanta, the sclc planned to hold its ninth annual ``drum major for justice'' awards dinner monday night. the event takes its title from a phrase king used to describe how he wished to be remembered. this year's honorees include u.s. rep. michael espy of mississippi, singer dionne warwick and washington redskins quarterback doug williams
sharissa fox, 17 and a senior at greensboro dudley high school in north carolina, worries that her generation may not hear king's story often and powerfully enough
black people have made progress since king's assassination, but i don't think we have gone as far as he would have liked,'' she said. ``his message was to help other people as much as we can. but my generation is so hooked on themselves, they don't have time.''
in portland, ore., nearly 100 people on saturday joined in a 1.5-mile walk to mark king's assassination on april 4, 1968
when people gather together there is hope,'' said ron herndon, co-director of portland's black united front. ``the message is there still are those who will stand up against racism.'' with mabn held without bail; picks up 5th graf, `sheriff's capt...'. subs 11-12th grafs, bgng `hatchett said...' with 4 grafs to add further detail from sheriff's spokesman. picks up 13th graf, `the three ...'</note>
a man apparently angry over a land dispute involving his former in-laws opened fire on mourners gathering for an easter sunday funeral, killing three and wounding three others including his ex-wife, authorities said
the shooting occurred in the parking lot of the mountain home baptist church, where family and friends gathered for a funeral service for effie collins justice, 79. the service had been scheduled to begin at 3 p.m., officials said, and the shooting took place shortly before that
it was just a really horrible experience, nothing i could ever have imagined,'' said lester justice, a nephew of mrs. justice. like most of the mourners, justice was already inside the small, brick rural church when the shooting began but could hear the gunfire
michael leslie rainey, 41, was charged with three counts of first-degree murder and three counts of assault with a deadly weapon with intent to kill, according to a release from the henderson county sheriff's department
rainey was being held without bond sunday evening in the henderson county jail, awaiting an initial court appearance set for monday morning
sheriff's capt. tom hatchett said the dead were the parents of rainey's ex-wife, along with a 24-year-old man whose relationship to the family was not immediately determined
the three, wilford owensby, 61, of fletcher; his wife, ponnelle, 60; and scott bowles, 24, were all pronounced dead at the scene, the sheriff's department said. mrs. owensby was mrs. justice's daughter
the suspect's former wife, andrea rainey, 40, of kennesaw, ga., was taken to margaret pardee hospital in hendersonville where she was listed in good condition with bullet wounds in the neck, said hospital spokeswoman mary ann morris
mrs. rainey's sister, sheila johnston, 30, of fletcher, and her daughter, wendy johnston, 11, were both listed in critical but stable condition at memorial mission hospital in asheville, said nursing supervisor evelyn woody. mrs. johnston was wounded in the chest, while her daughter was wounded in the leg, the hospital said
rainey apparently confronted his former wife and her relatives in the parking lot, hatchett said
there seems to be some sort of domestic thing, over conflict over some land,'' he said. the suspect owned land near the church which is adjacent to property belonging to mrs. rainey's family, he said
witnesses said the suspect walked into the church to view the body of mrs. justice, and then walked outside. mourners in the church then heard gunshots
i understand they were having visitation when he came to the church. he apparently had weapons in a vehicle outside the church. he went outside and got them out of the trunk and then started shooting,'' hatchett said
hatchett said rainey left the shooting scene on foot after dropping the weapons in the parking lot. he was arrested without incident a short distance away. two weapons were found in the parking lot, a handgun and a shotgun, hatchett said
witnesses said mrs. rainey drove herself and her wounded sister and niece away from the church after the shooting, and her ford sedan was riddled with bullet holes. the three were in the car when the shooting broke out, hatchett said
the three reached the hendersonville city limits, a few miles away, before authorities transferred them from the blood-stained car to ambulances
the funeral was canceled. police were still interviewing witnesses at the church sunday evening
edneyville is an unincorporated town in a rural area in the western part of the state, about 20 miles southeast of asheville. saturday violence. pickup 2nd graf pvs, `county supervisor...'</note>
police chief daryl gates vowed saturday to deploy 1,000 officers on gang-ridden south-central streets to keep easter churchgoers safe after a drive-by shooting in which one man died and 12 others were wounded
gang violence erupted later in the day when two gang members were wounded by gunfire after a confrontation between rival groups in a downtown parking lot, said police lt. orley barton
the victims, both 21, were taken to los angeles county-usc medical center. a spokeswoman said one was in fair condition with a gunshot wound in the foot and the second, who was hit in the buttocks, was listed as serious
county supervisor kenneth hahn sent a telegram to gov. george deukmejian urging him to declare a state of emergency in los angeles and send in two companies of military police from the california national guard
the people of los angeles county are increasingly living in a state of fear. no one is safe,'' he wrote
the governor is very concerned about the escalation of gang violence in los angeles county,'' said deukmejian's press secretary, kevin brett
however, he would declare a state of emergency only after the city and county governments proclaim that such an emergency exists and that it exceeds the capabilities of local law enforcement officials, brett said
no one had been arrested in friday's shooting, but gates said police were investigating leads on two men seen shooting from a passing car. one of those wounded was a 4-year-old boy
the shootings came in the midst of a police crackdown on escalating gang violence, which only a day earlier prompted one los angeles county supervisor to call for help from the california national guard
if we were angry before, we are exceedingly angry now,'' gates said at a news conference where he called gang members ``rotten little cowards ... who shoot down 4-year-old kids.''
plans were under way to put 1,000 officers on south-central streets where 200 officers usually patrol, gates said, adding that 300 officers would be out saturday night
we have all this shooting going on on the holy weekend. people in south-central l.a. want to go to church tomorrow and we're going to make sure they're safe,'' gates said
he also called for night sessions at all courts in order to speed up trials and put criminals behind bars, special courts to handle gang and narcotic cases, and a south-central justice center
lt. charles massey said friday's shots were fired on turf claimed by five or six gangs, and that the shootings probably were intended as some type of retaliation. police believe a semi-automatic weapon was used
rodney bragg, 16, said he saw men in a cadillac stop and talk to a group of people
all of a sudden they just opened up,'' he said. ``there were about 20 shots, i guess. maybe more than that. you could hear them hitting the trees and the houses _ everything.''
the car sped off and then returned ``for another look'' before fleeing, bragg said
at least 25 rounds were fired, gates said
cmdr. william booth said 13 people were hit. only 11 were accounted for at local hospitals. authorities said two people may have sought medical attention on their own
seven anti-gang police sweeps through the city in the past month, including one through the southside thursday night, have resulted in 874 arrests and seizures of weapons, drugs, cash and cars
on thursday, county supervisor kenneth hahn asked gov. george deukmejian to call in the national guard to help quell gang violence
hahn cited 387 gang-related deaths within the county last year and said the gang-related death rate in the first three months of 1988 exceeds the rate for the same period last year
however, since the sweeps, the tally of gang-related homicides apparently has decreased, from 25 in march 1987 to 14 in march 1988, police said. his life</head>
a former british fighter pilot was reported sunday as saying austrian president kurt waldheim saved his life and those of other allied prisoners during world war ii by preventing them falling into the hands of nazi executioners
the sunday times said the pilot, bruce ogilvie, is the ``first and possibly the only british ex-serviceman to speak in defense of waldheim,'' who denies accusations of involvement in war crimes when he was serving with the german army
ogilvie, now 66, said he was in danger of being shot when he was found armed and in civilian clothes on the british-occupied greek island of leros in november 1943, the day after german paratroops invaded
he said he was taken to an airfield outside athens where he met waldheim, who introduced himself by name and ensured that ogilvie and others were sent to a prisoner-of-war camp instead of the nazi ss, who shot prisoners
ogilvie said waldheim took the prisoners' identity discs and gave them substitutes which had been taken from the bodies of allied servicemen killed in action. the discs enabled the prisoners to prove they were not commandos or spies
ogilvie said he mentioned waldheim's help to royal air officers who debriefed him after his release from a prison camp in may 1945
thousands of cyclists, joggers and sightseers turned out saturday and sunday to cross japan's majestic seto ohashi bridge, which straddles five small islands over an expanse of 7.6 miles in the seto inland sea
police bands performed and hundreds of balloons were set off as seto bridge authorities feted to mark the completion of the first physical linkup between the main island of honshu and shikoku island, located on the pacific side of southeastern japan
about 100,000 pedestrians, selected by lottery from around the country, formed a human link between shikoku and honshu on the bridge at noon sunday
on saturday, 3,000 people crossed the ohashi (literally great bridge) on bicycles, while an estimated 7,000-8,000 joggers joined in later the same day
the bridge, which cost $8.7 billion and took 10 years to build, will open to both rail and vehicle traffic after the official opening april 10
transportation officials acknowledge that while the railway portion of the bridge is not expected to recoup its construction costs, toll charges for the highway section of the bridge should help to keep operation costs near or above deficit levels
the seto ohashi bridge, consisting of six suspension bridges in the style of san francisco's golden gate bridge, will be formally connected to that californian symbol in a sister bridge ceremony scheduled for tuesday
three moderate overnight quakes shook the greek capital, frightening some residents out of their homes but causing no damage or injuries, officials said sunday
a spokesman for the athens seismological institute said the first temblor measured 4.2 on the richter scale at 11:06 p.m. saturday. it had its epicenter 12 miles east of athens, just outside the seaside resort town of loutsa
the second quake struck in the same area at 00:58 a.m. sunday and registered 4.6 on the richter scale
the third tremor, hitting 4.4 on the richter scale, took place at 06:35 a.m. sunday and had its its epicenter 47 miles west-northwest of athens
we had some minor panic and some people ran out of their homes and into the streets, but we had no damage,'' said a police spokesman in loutsa
the earthquakes, felt all over the capital, did not cause much panic, athens police said
we had alot of people call in to see what happened but we had no reports of serious panic,'' an athens police spokesman said
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. a magnitude 4 quake can cause moderate damage
the soviet union set off an underground nuclear test explosion early sunday in the republic of kazakhstan, the official tass news agency reported
the blast, the third nuclear test announced by the soviets this year, was ``carried out with a view to upgrading military technology,'' tass said
the explosion had a yield of 20 to 150 kilotons, tass said. the u.s. atom bomb dropped on hiroshima, japan, on aug. 6, 1945, had a yield of 20 kilotons, or the equivalent of 20,000 tons of tnt
the device was exploded at the soviet union's main nuclear testing range in semipalatinsk, in the central asian republic of kazakhstan
tass provided no further information on the blast
in january, an american scientific delegation visited the semipalatinsk range to gather information that may be used in verifying u.s.-soviet compliance with a future test ban
an exchange of visits to semipalatinsk and to the u.s. nuclear testing site in nevada is planned this month
the soviet government has been pressing for a pact prohibiting nuclear testing, but u.s. and soviet officials disagree on enforcement procedures. pole</head>
the army said an arab youth was electrocuted sunday when he tried to attach a palestinian flag to a utility pole. hospital officials said a second arab died of gunshot wounds suffered last week in a clash with israeli soldiers
the fatalities came hours before the scheduled arrival of secretary of state george p. shultz for a third round of talks with israeli leaders on his middle east peace initiative and while hundreds of christians celebrated easter in jerusalem
the deaths also occurred a day after israeli soldiers shot and killed six arab protesters in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, the highest one-day death toll in four months of unrest
the jerusalem post newspaper quoted military sources as saying the army has adopted a new policy of entering even remote arab villages to break up protests instead of ignoring demonstrators as long as they did not endanger lives or interfere with traffic on the main roads
the confrontations (over the weekend) were a result of our initiative,'' defense minister yitzhak rabin told israel radio
in jerusalem, about 1,000 pilgrims from around the world attended easter sunday services in the church of the holy sepulcher where most christians believe jesus was buried and rose from the dead
church officials said the number of worshipers dropped by half from last year, apparently because many pilgrims were scared away by the violence in the occupied territories
in the west bank town of tulkarem, 40 miles northwest of jerusalem, an army official said a 20-year-old arab youth died early sunday after being electrocuted when he tried to attach a red, white, black and green palestinian flag, outlawed by israel, to a utility pole
after receiving the shock, the youth fell from the pole and hit his head, said the official who, in keeping with army regulations, spoke on condition of anonymity. the youth was pronounced dead at tulkarem hospital
arab journalists identified the victim as 15-year-old mahmoud abdul rahim jarad and said he was shot to death by israeli soldiers
officials at tulkarem hospital could not immediately be reached for comment on the cause of death
at ramallah hospital, 10 miles north of jerusalem, a 40-year-old arab died sunday of wounds he suffered wednesday in a clash with israeli soldiers. during the clash, ali diab abu ali of the west bank village yatta, was shot in the neck and paralyzed, said a doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity
his death brought to 134 the number of arabs killed in four months of anti-israeli protests, according to u.n. figures. the youth from tulkarem was not included in the count because of conflicting reports on the circumstances of his death. one israeli soldier has died in the violence
shultz is scheduled to meet monday with rabin, prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres. israel radio quoted sources in egypt as saying shultz planned to present to israeli leaders an invitation to an international peace conference which is to launch direct bilateral negotiations between the parties to the conflict
shamir opposes key elements of the shultz plan, especially a proposed international conference. the jerusalem post quoted a shamir aide as saying ``if shultz doesn't present any new ideas in his talks with shamir ... , the prime minister will not budge.''
peres supports the shultz plan
pope john paul ii celebrated easter sunday mass in st. peter's basilica, then appealed for world peace and offered easter greetings in 52 languages to thousands of worshipers in rain-drenched st. peter's square
among the thousands of people who packed christendom's biggest church for the mass was u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, who was to leave later in the day for israel on a new middle east peace mission
the mass, usually held on the flower-decked travertine steps of st. peter's, was moved inside the church because of rain. but the pope later spoke from the church's central balcony as more than 100,000 people stood in the square below
in his traditional easter message ``urbi and orbi'' (to the city of rome and the world) following the mass, the pope asked the virgin mary to pray for peace, justice, human rights and religious freedom
departing from his written text and speaking emotionally in a strong, hoarse voice, the pontiff said, ``pray for peace in the world, for justice, pray for the rights of man, especially for religious freedom, for every man, for every christian and non-christian, pray for us.''
pray for the solidarity of all peoples of the world, the first world, second, third and fourth, all the world,'' he said. ``in yours and our easter joy, we carry again this weight of humanity, this weight of so many human hearts, our brothers, our sisters, and we repeat: pray for us.''
in a private audience on saturday, shultz had received the pope's blessing for his voyage
shultz's wife, helena, a roman catholic, was one of those taking communion from the pope
winter weather descended on rome this weekend, with a cold, steady rain drenching the capital sunday morning
it was decided at the last moment to move the service inside the basilica, where the pope celebrated mass from an altar under the ``baldacchino,'' the immense baroque canopy designed by bernini
the italian news agency ansa estimated that 150,000 romans, pilgrims and tourists _ most of them huddling under umbrellas _ stood outside in the square and its side streets and listened to the service broadcast on loud speakers by radio vatican
the crowd broke into loud cheers and chants of ``viva il papa'' (long live the pope) when john paul, keeping with tradition, appeared on the central balcony at noon to deliver his easter message and blessing
the message was directed to the virgin mary, for whom the pope has a special devotion and dedicated the current marian year
christ whom you bore is risen, alleluia,'' said the pope, wearing a white robe trimmed in gold and a tall, gold miter, or bishop's hat. ``queen of heaven, rejoice. this is the day of the church's easter joy. we all share in your glory, oh mother.''
behold the whole church today tooks to you, oh mary. even though we do not see you among the people about whom the accounts of easter tell, we all look to you ..
during this year, which has been dedicated in a particular way to you, during this marian year, be present in a special way in the church..''
then, following his improvised plea for world peace, the polyglot pope wished the world a happy easter in 52 languages. the longest greeting was in his native polish
iraq said its warplanes raided two oil refineries deep inside iran on sunday, but iran said the bombs landed in residential areas and killed at least five civilians and wounded 50 more
the attacks signaled the rekindling of the ``war of the cities'' after a break of 2{ days. hundreds of civilians have been killed or wounded in more than a month of missile and warplane raids on major population centers
the official iraqi news agency quoted a military communique as saying the strikes on the refineries near the cities of isfahan and tabriz were carried out at 2:40 p.m
that was about six hours after turkish prime minister turgut ozal left the iraqi capital. baghdad had ceased its attacks on iranian cities during his visit and announced it would not resume attacks for six hours after he left
iran's islamic republic news agency said the warplanes bombed residential quarters in tabriz, in northeastern iran, and the central city of isfahan
at least five civilians were killed and 50 wounded, said the news agency report. the iranian and iraqi dispatches were monitored in cyprus
the iranian agency claimed that anti-aircraft batteries shot down one of the warplanes at isfahan ``seconds after the attack'' on the city
it did not say where the plane fell nor disclose the fate of the pilot. iraq had no comment on the claim
two moscow factory managers were expelled from the communist party for embezzlement, on-the-job drinking parties and paying $1.6 million to two hockey players who masqueraded as machine operators, a soviet newspaper said sunday
the report in pravda, the official paper of the communist party, was taken to be a message to party members at all state industries
pravda also reported that party's control committee had disciplined two officials of the state ministry for aviation machine-building involved in the errant enterprise
the report said the managers of the salyut air transport machine-building enterprise engaged in embezzlement but it did not give a total figure for the losses suffered by the factory
still, the newspaper gave several examples of excesses that cost in the tens of thousands of dollars, indicating the violations were broad
factory director y.v. pugin and party committee chairman a.g. samarkin were expelled, and other senior party officials at the plant and the ministry were reprimanded, the newspaper said
under soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms aimed at improving economic performance, party members have come under close scrutiny
only about 8 percent of soviet adults gain entrance into the all-powerful party, and the control commission is charged with ensuring that communists set an appropriate example for other workers
stories about the abuse of authority and inattention to the cause of poor performance have become common as the party carries out internal reviews of its personnel
