the woman was crushed to death by a falling chuck of concrete. one of the 14 injured was reported in serious condition
the explosion occurred at about 3 a.m. and devastated the second, third and fourth floors of the nine-story building
the other residents of the building were evacuated
salon-de-provence, france (ap) _ a spanish bus carrying 53 people sunday slammed into a small truck that stopped on a highway because of a flat tire. police said the drivers of both vehicles were killed
the truck's driver had stopped in the right line to repair the flat tire and one of its four occupants tried to alert traffic, police said
the spanish bus, traveling in the same direction, hit the truck from behind and killed its driver, 32-year-old bouhid abdellati. the driver of the bus, eduardo asensio arribas, 61, also was killed
the three other occupants of the truck suffered no injuries
twenty-six passengers on the bus were slightly injured and taken to local hospitals. they were identified as teen-agers from a religious school in saragosa. uplifted</head>
jesse jackson, accustomed to bringing an uplifting message to the downtrodden, found a warm reception among the already uplifted at this chic ski playground
looking to win delegates in mondays' colorado democratic caucuses, jackson dropped in on the sunny, snowy resort high in the rocky mountains on saturday afternoon
it was a visit that took the black civil rights leader and presidential candidate a long way from his usual audiences _ like the hispanics who surged to touch him in pueblo, and the striking meatpackers in greeley who cheered wildly to his denunciation of the rich and powerful earlier in the day
i was surprised he came here,'' said mary scheerer, a tanned and blond frequent visitor from minneapolis who strained to get jackson in the sights of her video camera as he arrived. ``i guess it's because the mayor invited him.''
jackson was greeted by the town's white, bearded mayor, bill stirling, a local real estate man who sported a jackson bumper sticker across his white cowboy hat. later, wearing a blue pin-stripe suit and bow tie, he danced and sang along with a recorded campaign song after introducing the candidate
people have said, `why aspen?' it's too glitzy, too lily white, too middle class,'' the mayor said, his last remark drawing laughter. ``well, we vote here too.''
arriving after a day of skiing was tom hayden, the california legislator and husband of actress jane fonda. he wasn't endorsing jackson, he said, but he had nice things to say about him
the gathering spilled out the door from the ornate room in the old jerome hotel, a recently restored three-story brick building that looks like it came straight out of the old west _ but updated for the ski crowd. to get to jackson's speech, people walked past guests frolicking in the hotel's outdoor hot tub and through a bar with a giant chandelier made of antlers
some who turned out were supporters, and some just seemed curious. many wore bright ski suits
one man dressed in cowboy shirt and hat, face red from skiing, said on his way in: ``we're here for both _ jesse and the fashion show.'' he said there really was a fashion show in town, but he might have been talking about the affluent, all-white crowd's wardrobe
others claimed to be real supporters. at the pitkin county airport, where the idle private jets of aspen's visitors wait in rows, andrea hanson was among the handful of greeters
i just think he's the best thing going,'' said hanson, clad in a black leather miniskirt. she described herself as an author of children's books
posters printed by local supporters invited people to see jackson. included was a notice that the reception beforehand was ``for substantial contributors only ($100 to $1,000).''
jackson spoke passionately, as usual, of the poor, but at the same time responded to his monied audience. the poor work, he said, and are all around, even in aspen
they changed the sheets in the hotel you slept in last night,'' he said
the upper class cannot remain upper if there is not a middle class,'' he told the substantial contributors
one man put a tough question to jackson: did he back raising taxes as high as 60 percent on upper incomes like his own? it would discourage the creation of jobs, he said
to tax you 60 percent would be as absurd as a tax cut,'' responded jackson, who hours earlier had denounced president reagan for ``reverse robin hood'' _ taking from the poor for the rich. jackson suggested the tax rates before president reagan's 1981 tax cut were reasonable
with the larger crowd, jackson didn't miss an opportunity to ask for contributions to his campaign
give like you live _ high,'' jackson said
jackson led in responsive chants as he does with other audiences _ evoking such shouts as ``vote'' and ``jesse.'' when they didn't get it right, he interrupted: ``let's stop and do it right, do it with rhythm and soul.''
a few feet to the side, hayden was talking politics and speculating on a mario cuomo-jesse jackson ticket
something very powerful is happening,'' hayden said. ``i don't know if he can win in november, but nobody else is having an effect like this.''
jackson seemed to enjoy his visit, too. the chanting done, jackson grinned and waved
okay, aspen,'' he said
a military exhibit at a popular south african festival includes a detailed demonstration on how to plant and detect land mines
the south african defense force exhibit is part of the grand rand show, a three-week festival that began wednesday on the outskirts of johannesburg
the large military display includes a section with a south african soldier explaining how land mines work and how the military detects them
visitors are allowed to handle the mine detector and wear the headset that gives off a beeping noise when a dummy mine is detected
if someone steps on the dummy mine, it gives off a harmless puff of green smoke. the soldier at the exhibit also explains the proper way to plant and disguise a land mine
guerrillas of the african national congress often employ land mines as part of their bombing and sabotage campaign to overthrow the white-led government
