paolo milano, a professor and prominent literary critic, has died after a long illness. he was 84
milano, who died of parkinson's disease saturday in rome, was described by the city's daily la repubblica on sunday as ``one of the most cosmopolitan voices of italian culture.''
born in rome in 1904, milano, a jew, fled the italian fascist regime in the late 1930s. after a brief period in paris, he settled in new york in 1940
he lived there for 15 years teaching comparative literature at queens college and at the new school of social research
he edited ``the portable dante,'' published in 1947, and wrote ``henry james _ the voluntary exile,'' which came out in 1948. he also contributed articles to such publications as politics, the partisan review and the nation
from 1957 to 1986, milan worked in rome as literary critic of the italian weekly magazine l'espresso
his funeral was scheduled for tuesday in the jewish cemetery of rome. survivors are his wife, rachel, of new york; a son andrew, of scarsdale, n.y.; and three grandchildren
three moderate earthquakes shook athenians awake saturday and sunday while another strong temblor rocked the western resort island of corfu
none of the quakes caused injuries or damage, authorities said
a spokesman for the athens seismological institute said a strong quake measuring 5.0 on the richter scale occurred at 11:56 a.m. sunday. its epicenter was 212 miles northwest of athens in the seabed off the island of corfu
the popular resort island has about 2,000 mostly british tourists visiting over the easter holiday, local police said
three other quakes registering 4.2, 4.6 and 4.4 on the richter scale rumbled through the greek capital between 11 p.m. saturday and 7 a.m. sunday
the four quakes are not geologically connected, we rule out the chance of a disastrous quake coming from any of the areas ... so people shouldn't panic,'' professor yiannis dracopoulos, greece's senior seismologist, told state-run television
the athens region has 3.5 million residents, a third of greece's population
the first two quakes had their epicenters 12.5 miles east of athens in the seabed off the coastal town of loutsa, while the third had its epicenter 47 miles northwest of the capital
an athens police spokesman said the three quakes were felt throughout the capital, but didn't cause any injuries or damage
we had a lot of people calling in to find out what was happening but nobody panicked,'' said a police spokesman who requested anonymity
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. a magnitude 4 quake can cause moderate damage while a force 5 temblor can cause considerable damage
under police and army guard, pilgrims from around the world gathered at dawn for easter sunday services in the church marking the site where most christians believe jesus rose from the dead
about 1,000 worshipers _ half as many as last year _ attended services in the 12th century church of the holy sepulcher, church officials said
many pilgrims were scared away by four months of almost daily violence in the israeli-occupied territories that have left more than 130 palestinians and one israeli soldier dead. the greek orthodox church canceled three pre-easter processions scheduled for the weekend
security was low-key sunday at the crusader-built church, where about half a dozen uniformed police stood guard in the courtyard and at the entrance
but dozens of soldiers were stationed throughout the walled old city, some on rooftops and others patrolling the narrow cobblestone streets. an arab attacker stabbed an israeli policeman in the old city on friday
before we came, our friends were worried and said they would pray for us,'' said 71-year-old arnold rosenbrock, a lutheran from kankakee, ill
we've been fine, but someone was killed in bethlehem yesterday (saturday) a few hours before we visited,'' he added. ``there were boulders in the street, and it was tense.''
we were frightened before we came, but now that we are here, we feel it is safe,'' said philip jiamachello, 31, of houston, texas, who attended the services with his wife and young son. ``for me, this was a very moving experience.''
tourism ministry officials said they had no figures for the month of march, but acknowledged a 13 percent drop in tourism for the first week of the month as compared with a year ago. officials also expressed concern about possible cancellations in april and may
clouds of incense and organ music filled the church during the latin service held in front of the marble-enclosed tomb marking the site where jesus is believed to have been resurrected
the roman catholic patriarch of jerusalem, monsignor michel sabbah, the first palestinian to hold the post, presided over the service. last week, he called on worshipers to make special easter prayers for those caught up in the arab-israeli conflict
at the church entrance, visiting pilgrims kissed and pressed their foreheads to the rose-colored marble stone where followers are believed to have washed jesus' body before his burial
several worshipers dropped handkerchiefs to soak up some of the holy water that dampens the stone
others walked upstairs to the candle-lit table marking the site where jesus' cross is believed to have been buried
one feels very humble walking on the same soil where christ walked,'' said gale crisher, 48, of long island, n.y. ``my children couldn't believe i was coming to israel now, but i felt have very comfortable here.''
while the roman catholics were celebrating easter, orthodox denominations were marking their palm sunday, walking along the via dolorosa, or way of sorrow, where jesus, wearing a crown of thorns, was forced to carry the cross on which he died. orthodox christians celebrate easter this coming sunday
in the midst of the easter service, about two dozen chanting coptic priests and choir boys in long dark robes entered the church carrying palm leaves, some formed in the shape of a cross
easter also fell on the third day of the jewish holiday of passover, commemorating the deliverance of the ancient hebrews from slavery in egypt
palestinian shopkeepers opened stores around the church from morning until noon, the times permitted by the palestine liberation organization. the plo has ordered afternoon strikes in arab east jerusalem to protest the israeli occupation
but even merchants who remained open complained there was little business
i sold about $1,000 worth of items a day last year during holy week. this year, i'm lucky if it is $100,'' said mike mannix, a jerusalem-born palestinian and owner of a shop selling olive-wood crosses and icons
last easter my store was filled to the doorway and people were crowded on the streets outside,'' the 32-year-old mannix added. ``this year, there is no one.''
two years after a u.s. bombing raid shocked the nation, libyans are breathing a bit easier
moammar gadhafi, their leader and the target of the attack, is permitting some long-awaited, though small steps to fix the economy. he is also calling for greater personal liberty
and it's true, right, that reagan can't become president again?'' asked a libyan military man, confident that life is looking up for his countrymen
for the u.s. president, col. gadhafi was the ``mad dog of the middle east'' and a sponsor of terrorism, including 1985 attacks on airports in rome and vienna. to gadhafi, reagan was the ``israeli dog'' in the ``black house,'' the villain behind the april 15, 1986, bombing, which libyans say killed the colonel's baby daughter and 36 other people
the good-guy, bad-guy rhetoric drew attention from an economy badly needing direction, especially after falling oil prices flattened libya's plump cushion of petroleum income. the global theater also overshadowed the growing demands of libyan consumers
now gadhafi seems bent on ensuring his popularity by improving life for his more than 3.5 million countrymen in the north african nation
of course, motives are often difficult to judge in the case of the mercurial colonel who came to power in a 1969 coup and who is now simply called ``the leader'' by libyans
some observers think the 45-year-old gadhafi may have decided to reform his virulent anti-americanism, which sometimes made him an easy target of u.s. outrage. others think gadhafi may also have been affected by an amnesty international appeal in july to end an alleged policy of assassinating opposition figures
while slogans denouncing purported american aggression are still plastered on buildings, one diplomat says that there has been a quiet exchange of messages between the u.s. and libyan governments indicating a desire, if not to improve relations, at least to keep channels open
there are several signs gadhafi may also have decided to push for a more liberal economy
a tripoli newspaper last month reported that small businesses are now permitted to import items, such as automobile parts, previously allowed only for government-franchise holders, and sell them at a profit. diplomats were apparently told to improve distribution of consumer goods, and more private businesses were allowed to operate
insisting repeatedly that libyans must produce for themselves, gadhafi has tried to reduce dependence on imports, especially after libya's oil revenues dropped dramatically from a 1980 peak of $22 billion
by 1986, lower oil prices saw annual revenue plummet to less than $6 billion. prospects for slightly higher oil prices this year could put income at about $6.5 billion
on tripoli's shopping streets, business seems to have grown over the past year. freshly slaughtered fat chickens hang from doorways enticing customers. women _ some shrouded head-to-toe in white cotton, others in form-fitting, olive green military pants and jackets _ examine satin-striped fabric, while men try out imported calculators
it seems every other store window has cheap leather shoes, vinyl pocketbooks and suitcases
a diplomat reports that in the past year the government, which likes to boast of an extensive health care system, is allowing libyans to buy western currency and go abroad, ostensibly for medical treatment
one thing that hasn't changed in libya, though, is the ground rule of anonymity which covers conversations with diplomats, businessmen and the few libyans willing to give their reading on what's happening
gadhafi has been focusing as well on personal liberties
one afternoon last month, the masterful user of the media rode a bulldozer to knock down the gate of a tripoli prison. to the cheers of one of the largest rallies in the capital in years, according to a diplomat, gadhafi declared that the released inmates included some who had plotted to kill him
a week later, gadhafi called for abolishing the death penalty in a nation where hangings have been broadcast on state television
on march 28, gafhafi announced that all arrests should be backed by a court order
this is a very good thing,'' said a smiling libyan, relaxing in a lounge a few hours after the speech. ``now members of the revolutionary committees just come up and take people away without warning.''
the committees are gadhafi's watchdogs of revolutionary ideology
gadhafi also announced he is withdrawing troops from eastern libya as a goodwill gesture toward its eastern neighbor, egypt, with which it has been feuding for 15 years
communist rebels suffered a major setback with the recent arrest of their top leaders, but military officials and analysts say the insurgents are far from beaten
through their 19-year rebellion, the guerrillas have demonstrated remarkable resilience. despite harsh crackdowns, their influence has spread from the countryside to urban centers, attacks have stepped up and captured leaders have been replaced immediately
president corazon aquino, who has vowed to crush the insurgency before her term expires in 1992, hailed last tuesday's arrests of the new people's army commander and the communist party's no. 2 man as the beginning of the end
it clearly demonstrates that we have turned the tide and are winning the war against the communist insurgency,'' she said in a statement
but military officials and others say the president may have spoken too soon, although they acknowledge that the arrests were a big blow to the 25,000-strong guerrilla army
it will disturb some of their programs,'' brig. gen. rodolfo biazon, manila area commander, said of the arrests. ``but to say that this means the defeat of the communist movement may not entirely be correct because we are fighting an idea, and the idea is still there.''
francisco tatad, a columnist and former information minister under ousted president ferdinand marcos, noted the insurgents not only survived but expanded after the capture of party founder jose maria sison and former rebel commander bernabe buscayno in the mid-1970s
tatad said the rebels now enjoy broad support among workers, students, the clergy and other groups in society and that the government must improve its services ``to make the very idea of insurgency obsolete.''
still, the arrests of rebel commander romulo kintanar, secretary-general rafael baylosis and four other rebels marked a dramatic success for the government
they came as the military was on alert for rebel attacks marking last tuesday's 19th anniversary of the rebel force. instead it was the military which struck, raiding communist hideouts in the capital
the arrest of kintanar, 37, is especially significant. kintanar, a master guerrilla strategist, was widely believed to have organized assassination squads known as ``sparrow units,'' which brought the guerrilla conflict from the countryside to the cities
police say up to 4,000 sparrows are deployed in metropolitan manila, where they have killed more than 150 police, soldiers and government officials since january 1987
veteran journalist max soliven wrote in the philippine star that for the first time in years, the rebels are ``now sweating it out.'' but he warned against complacency
the rebels ``are so desperate at this juncture that they may unleash a series of furious attacks and ambushes, just to create the impression that the movement remains strong,'' soliven wrote
sen. rene saguisag, mrs. aquino's former spokesman, agreed it was too early to say whether the arrests have dealt a fatal blow to the insurgency
saguisag said one factor favoring the government is mrs. aquino's continued popularity. another, he said, was the ongoing attempt to hammer out a land reform act
he said since mrs. aquino took over from marcos on feb. 25, 1986, she has introduced broad social and economic reforms. saguisag acknowledged that substantial disaffection remains but ``it is nowhere like the disenchantment with marcos, which was across the board.''
even more than a debacle for the rebels, the arrests are seen as a morale booster for the underpaid, ill-equipped armed forces of the philippines. since mrs. aquino took office when a military-civilian uprising deposed marcos, the 160,000-member armed forces has been wracked by divisions that resulted in at least half a dozen coup attempts
defense secretary fidel v. ramos says those days are over. he said the arrests show the military is now a united, effective force
ramos spoke before the escape saturday of former lt. col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan, leader of a failed coup attempt in august. many filipinos saw the escape as a blow to the prestige and unity of the armed forces
the significance of tuesday's arrests may well depend on the accuracy of intelligence reports of a bitter power struggle within rebel ranks
according to military officials, the infighting is between those favoring violent struggle and others who want the movement to expand politically among the rural population
brig. gen. alexander aguirre, the capital's chief law enforcer, predicted that tuesday's arrests will deepen divisions among the rebels because each faction will blame the other for the setback
much also depends on how much foreign assistance flows to the rebels. military officials say the funds come from leftist groups in western europe, australia, new zealand and the united states
richard armitage, u.s. assistant defense secretary, told a congressional committee in washington this week that the soviets were sending money. soviet diplomats here deny the charge
miguel c. suarez is manila news editor for the associated press and has been reporting on events in the philippines since 1970
gen. manuel antonio noriega, the indicted strongman of panama, may be running out of time and options in his stubborn quest to remain in power
the man president reagan once called a ``tin-horn dictator'' so far has relied on brute force, threats and intimidation to maintain his grip on the nation
but despite another harsh crackdown on his opposition last week, many diplomatic and other observers feel noriega can count his remaining days on his fingers and toes
he really doesn't have anywhere to turn,'' said one western diplomat late last week. ``he is almost totally without meaningful support, either within the country or abroad.''
still, noriega has withstood four weeks of mounting economic pressure with such mulish defiance that another foreign diplomat, also speaking on condition of anonymity, was led to comment:
this guy's proving to be harder to get rid of than fleas on a dog. the problem is becoming one of whether you have to kill the dog before the fleas will leave.''
even elliott abrams, the state department official masterminding the u.s. effort to oust noriega, acknowledged last week that he and others in the reagan administration had misjudged the general's staying power
abrams, the assistant secretary of state for latin american affairs, said the miscalculation was based in part on the successful use of economic pressure to remove presidents ferdinand e. marcos from the philippines and jean-claude duvalier from haiti
the united states has cut off all economic and military aid to panama, withheld about $6.5 million a month in user fees from the panama canal, helped tie up more than $50 million in government funds on deposit in u.s. banks and eliminated some trade preferences
abrams suggested the time had come to consider even harsher economic sanctions, up to a total trade embargo. that's a bridge the administration so far has been unwilling to cross for fear of so badly damaging the country that a post-noriega government would be unable to pick up the pieces
we now realize that it is easier to remove civilian dictators than military ones,'' abrams said. ``in analogous circumstances, marcos and duvalier were gone already.''
some foreign diplomats in panama don't see the situation here as analogous to the philippines and haiti, regardless of any possible differences between civilian and military dictators
in the philippines, you had a cory aquino, who provided a rallying point,'' said one, referring to philippines president corazon aquino. ``there's nobody like that here. there also aren't many people here who appear willing to risk their lives in the struggle. in the philippines and haiti we saw desperate people acting desperately.''
the diplomats and two private economists, all of whom spoke on condition of anonymity, agreed there is little chance of u.s. military intervention, despite reagan's decision late last week to send an additional 1,300 soldiers to panama to help the 10,500 already here guard the panama canal and protect american civilians
indeed, only a day before reagan announced his decision to send the new troops, the panamanian government issued a communique saying it had no intention of provking an excuse for u.s. military action
the diplomats and economists also agreed unanimously that noriega's days are numbered by a rapidly souring economy that already has the general trapped in a fiscal maze with no outlet
panama went bankrupt last year, unable to make interest payments to any of the lenders to whom it owes $4.8 billion, one of the highest per capita debts in the world
then, early this year, noriega was indicted by two federal grand juries in florida that accused him of selling out his country to colombian drug traffickers in exchange for millions of dollars in bribes
after some weeks of apparent soul searching, panama's president, eric arturo delvalle, called for noriega's dismissal, only to have the effort backfire with his own ouster in a thinly disguised coup orchestrated by the general
three weeks ago, abrams' chief deputy, william walker, and a state department legal officer came to panama and offered noriega a deal: accept offered asylum in spain and the united states will not pursue you
the general refused
delvalle's ouster triggered a run on banks that forced their closure. the government, short of cash, could not pay its employees. some disgruntled officers tried but failed to overthrow noriega. and his civilian opposition heaped coals on the fire with a two-week general strike that began to crumble only late last week
even with the anticipated reopening of most industries and businesses this week, the government and its people are so short of money and so unlikely to get a big cash infusion that there is no hope of a return to ``normalcy'' anytime soon
what we're seeing here is a revolution in slow motion,'' said one diplomat. ``it may be taking longer than anyone expected, but it's happening.''
reid g. miller has been covering central america from san jose, costa rica, since january 1984. officers</head>
police patiently watched a stolen motorcycle for 17 days, 24 hours a day, in hopes of catching a burglar linked to nearly 200 break-ins, until one officer took a two-minute restroom break and the bike disappeared
two alachua county sheriff's investigators involved in the failed surveillance were placed on six months of probation
the so-called interstate 75 cat burglar, a cocky thief who police believe has occasionally helped himself to a snack while his victims slept soundly, has been linked to more than 180 break-ins in seven florida counties along i-75. he remains at large
alachua county investigators had their best shot at catching him in january, when a motorcycle stolen in citrus county during one of the cat burglar's sprees was found at a gainesville apartment complex, the gainesville sun reported saturday
teams of officers kept watch over the motorcycle from a motor home 125 yards away to see if the burglar would return to use it
but sgt. william ``bear'' bryan and investigator tony canchola said friday that a combination of incredible luck on the burglar's part and a poor line of sight from their vantage point combined to doom the surveillance
the $2,000 motorcycle was discovered parked at the apartment complex on jan. 9. one resident remembered seeing a man drive away on it on the same day the cat burglar struck a gainesville neighborhood, and it was later returned to the complex
bryan and canchola said the discovery of the motorcycle was the only real break in the i-75 cat burglar cases, which have frustrated authorities since november
so two deputies at a time kept vigil, with the aid of a television camera and night-vision scope
bryan and canchola even took the precaution of disabling the motorcycle's engine so it couldn't be started
on jan. 16, canchola was watching the tv monitor while bryan sat in the back of the motor home repairing other surveillance equipment, they said friday. canchola saw no one near the motorcycle, so he went to the bathroom for about two minutes. by the time both men got back to the monitor, the motorcycle was gone
we were so shocked that we were laughing,'' canchola said. ``we thought somebody had moved the motorcycle and was playing a joke on us.''
interviews with witnesses later revealed the cat burglar had snatched the motorcycle in a matter of seconds
the suspect drove up in a small pickup truck and parked just out of the investigators' line of sight. then, without trying to start the disabled motorcycle, he wheeled it to his truck and lifted it in the back
the cat burglar did not hit gainesville that night, when law-enforcement agencies were at full alert
the motorcycle was later found abandoned in port orange, south of daytona beach. alachua county sheriff's spokesman spencer mann said that city had several night burglaries at that time, but they have not been positively linked to the i-75 cat burglar
canchola and bryan wound up on probation and said friday they still feel bad about losing their best chance at collaring the burglar
if we'd have caught him, we'd have been heroes,'' bryan said
instead, ``we just got burned this time,'' canchola said
lebanon, long known as a supplier of hashish, has become one of the world's big heroin centers in the past few years as its economy and central government have collapsed, u.s. officials said
almost all the militias are involved in some way in the trafficking of drugs,'' one intelligence official said
several officials _ from the cia, the drug enforcement agency and the state department _ agreed to provide an overview of the drug situation in lebanon on the condition their names not be used
lebanon's role in the world's drug trade is discussed in the state department's march report on narcotics
lebanon is reportedly the world's major producer of hashish, as well as a key processing and transit point for heroin,'' the department said in its report, called ``international narcotics control strategy report.''
although lebanon has yet to approach places like colombia, pakistan and mexico in the volume of its drug trade, officials said the situation is worrisome because the united states has virtually no influence in the country, much of which is controlled by christian, druze and moslem factions
the united states has few statistics about lebanon's drug trade, but it reportedly is a more than $200 million-a-year business. the christians have long dominated the country's drug business, but other sects have moved into the business
syria, one of four countries under u.s. sanctions for failing to cooperate in the war on drugs, has peace-keeping troops in parts of lebanon. the other countries on the sanctions list are iran, panama and afghanistan
so chaotic is the situation in lebanon that yonah alexander, an expert on drugs and terrorism, described the country as ``turning back to the middle ages.'' alexander is at the center for strategic and international studies, a think tank
the central government ... has little control over the countryside where armed militia factions and syria hold sway,'' the state department said in its report
the department said that much of lebanon's drug activity occurs in the fertile bekaa valley, a region that is controlled by the syrian military and was once the country's breadbasket
syrian military officers ``profit from the trade and protect it,'' the report said
the hezbollah, a pro-iranian faction of shiite moslems thought to hold some of the american hostages in lebanon, also has bases and support in the bekaa. in 1986, dea agents were involved in a failed attempt to contact and pay the kidnappers in exchange for hostages
poppy cultivation has replaced the growing of fruits and vegetables in some of the bekaa's fields, and farmers find it easier to make money cultivating drugs and producing foodstuffs, officials say
we have seen over the last few years a shift from traditional agricultural products to ... more poppy,'' one department officer said. with decline of the lebanese pound, cultivating drugs has become a ``very lucrative, safe way of work,'' he said
growing drugs is less hassle for farmers, too. marketing is not a problem because the buyers often come to the source and pay cash, the official said
as a result of drug money, the bekaa has become a self-sufficient region within the tiny country, which is about the size of connecticut. ``the farmers are very independent,'' often setting up schools and buying big-ticket items like electric generating equipment, an american said
the bekaa has many of the country's heroin processing plants of which there are as many as 10. ``lebanon is not only a grower but also an importer of drugs,'' an american said. imported drugs come primarily from afghanistan and southeast asia
drugs are often shipped out of lebanon through ports controlled by various militias. the dea's interdiction program based in cyprus, about 60 miles off lebanon's coast, has successfully halted some trafficking
as a result, lebanese middlemen increasingly have relied on female couriers who leave the country overland through turkey or by plane with small amounts of drugs in body cavities or concealed in some fashion
drugs from lebanon usually end up in the united states, europe of egypt, officials say. but often couriers travel through africa before reaching their final destination, enforcement officials say
countries in west africa have large lebanese colonies. addis ababa, the ethiopia's capital, and nairobi, the kenya's capital, are favorite transit points for drug dealers from lebanon and elsewhere because of their good airport facilities, officials say
lebanon's burgeoning drug trade has led to more addicts inside the country, particularly among the militias and the young, college crowd. the bekaa farmers, however, seem to have little use for drug consumption
u.s. officials are not optimistic about making a dent in lebanon's drug trade anytime soon
a comprehensive eradication and interdiction program must await restoration of central government control,'' the state department's report said
official u.s. policy calls for national reconciliation in lebanon and removal of all foreign forces
but drugs contribute to the breakdown in central order by giving the militias and factions an outside source of income, making them more flexible and independent. the traditional way for the private militias to finance their operations is through local taxation
in the long run, this (drugs) contributes to the emerging partitioning of the country,'' one official said
the effort to push stock market crash legislation through congress before lawmakers become preoccupied with the summer political conventions has produced some strange bedfellows
nicholas brady, chairman of president reagan's task force on the crash, has teamed with two of the administration's sharpest critics: senate banking committee chairman william proxmire, d-wis., and rep. edward j. markey, d-mass., chairman of the house energy and commerce finance subcommittee
brady's republican credentials are impeccable. he is a former republican senator from new jersey, a member of vice president george bush's inner circle and a likely prospect for secretary of the treasury in a bush presidency
yet on the issue of reforming the nation's financial markets, he finds himself working closely with proxmire, whose ``golden fleece'' awards regularly skewer administration money-wasting, and markey, who made his name as a severe critic of the government's nuclear power bureaucracy and is now turning his attention to the regulation of the financial markets
arrayed against brady's proposals are three reagan appointees: federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan, securities and exchange commission chairman david ruder and commodity futures trading commission chairwoman wendy gramm
all three have praise for brady's research, but all three are vigorously opposing his proposals for changes in their agencies' jurisdiction
two months ago, under the glare of television lights in a senate hearing room, brady uttered his now well-known warning regarding the fragility of the stock market: ``we are looking down the barrel of a gun, and the gun is still loaded.''
since then, at every hearing the lanky wall street investment banker attends, he hears his words repeated by a democrat eager to prod a laissez faire reagan administration into action
brady would clearly like to see legislation providing more uniform regulation of the markets, but he is just as clearly uncomfortable at hearing his words used as a political club against the administration
after one hearing, where markey mixed lavish praise of brady with complaints of administration foot-dragging, brady joked to reporters: ``i didn't say anybody was going to pull the trigger.''
the administration has created a working group to resolve differences among the regulatory agencies. it is due to report to the president by mid-may
but both markey and proxmire have painted the creation of the group as a delaying tactic by an administration that doesn't want to offend entrenched interests and is prone to be skeptical of government regulation in the first place
brady says the working group isn't a bad idea, but nevertheless he has helped markey and proxmire write bills that will be finished before the administration is ready to make its recommendations
markey's bill is still being written, but proxmire introduced his on thursday. it would create an intermarket coordination committee and instruct the regulatory agencies to cooperate with it
opposition from the agencies as well as infighting among legislators representing competing interests make the bill's prospects appear dim
but because of brady's efforts, the sides are drawn less along party lines than some had expected
the day before proxmire introduced his bill, brady was on the floor of the senate drumming up support. as a result, five of the bill's seven co-sponsors are republicans
dave skidmore covers banking and financial issues in washington for the associated press
margie had a little lamb, little lamb, little lamb
then another and another
now, bill and marge lange's rare quintuplet lambs are the star attraction in this small town in southeastern north dakota
it was like grand central station,'' mrs. lange said. ``the day after they were born we had 10 people call to see if they were all right. i've had people bring their kids from town to see the lambs.''
the ewe was perplexed when she first got up and saw all those babies,'' she said. ``she looked one way and then the other. it was unreal.''
lamb quints are a rare event, occuring about once in 600,000 deliveries, said bert moore, professor of animal and range science at north dakota state university
the four females and one male are all healthy and hungry, mrs. lange said. the five are being fed by the ewe and bottle-fed with lamb milk replacement by mrs. lange, who said she feels like a mother again
i was a nervous wreck the first two days, but i'm fine now,'' she said. ``saturday night i had to go somewhere, so i called a babysitter to take care of my lambs. i get up every four hours at night to feed them. but they're eating more and more hay and oats, so soon i'll just feed them once a night.''
fecundity is in the blood line. the sire and the ewe were both triplets, so there's no telling how large a litter the newborn lambs may eventually have, mrs. lange said
for corrina clark, long distance really was the next best thing to being there
clark, who was in bartholomew county courthouse, married alvin mcgowan, who was at an army base in kaiserslaughtern, west germany, over the telephone thursday, exactly one year after the couple met by chance in houston
the bride, a native of indianapolis, said she wanted their marriage certificate to show that the ceremony took place in indiana
i've done a lot of marriages before, but never one by phone,'' said county clerk naomi jackson, who performed the ceremony. ``my last thing was `kiss the bride' and i couldn't say that.''
the couple will exchange vows in person, and seal it with a kiss, when they repeat the ceremony in paris this fall
the trans-atlantic telephone call was offered to the couple as a gift from columbus attorney richard eynon's office. investigate</head>
the federal communications commission has begun investigating two more california dial-a-porn services, but the agency says it is running out of complaints it can act on
i keep beating the bushes for new, specific complaints, but we just don't have a lot of them,'' though the agency gets plenty of general complaints about dial-a-porn, said greg vogt, chief of the fcc's telephone enforcement division
for the fcc to investigate possible violations of a federal law prohibiting transmission of sexually explicit messages to children, the agency needs information such as a phone bill and a statement that someone under 18 has reached the service without using a credit card, an access code or a descrambler, he said
i know there are violations out there, and i would love for concerned citizens to help us by bringing them to our attention because there is no way we can locate them in any other way,'' he said
the fcc has jurisdiction over dial-a-porn when the calls cross state lines or are to, from or within the district of columbia. local calls are under the jurisdiction of the state
complaints about dial-a-porn services have prompted many states to require telephone companies to block access to 976 and 900 numbers for residential customers who request it. phone companies also have been responding to public pressure to disconnect or otherwise limit the availability of these services
the fcc sent letters last week to two california adult-message services advising them of ``apparent'' violations. they were given 30 days to respond
if violations are found, the fcc could levy fines of up to $50,000 per day for each day a violation occurred
the companies cited are ramrod enterprises inc. of redding, calif., and 2001 enterprises of reseda, calif. neither company was listed with telephone directory assistance and the fcc said it was unable to obtain phone numbers for the companies or their owners
the actions against both companies stemmed from the same complaint that generated an investigation, begun last dec. 7, of another california provider of sexual messages, intercambio inc. of san jose, calif
the complaint was from parents of a 16-year-old connecticut boy who had made more than 280 calls to dial-a-porn services. the family was not identified
the complaint says the boy lost ``all respect for women in general'' as a result of the dial-a-porn messages he heard and is now seeing a psychiatrist
the fcc requires dial-a-porn providers to use an access code available only to adults or prepay with a credit card before they listen to the sexually explicit messages. the fcc also allows providers to scramble the messages so they can be heard only by someone with a descrambling device
the complaint against intercambio and a separate one citing audio enterprises of mill valley, calif., are pending while the commission re-evaluates the companies' messages in light of a federal appeals court ruling in january that the agency can restrict access only to obscene messages, but not indecent ones
the commission defines indecency as ``language or material that depicts or describes ... sexual or excretory activities or organs.''
obscene material must appeal to the prurient interest, depict or describe sexual conduct in a patently offensive way, and lack serious literary, artistic, political or scientific value
chinese army officers will trade in their mao suits for western-style jackets and ties this summer, the army newspaper said sunday
the liberation army daily said wang yingbo, one of the designers, described the new uniform as a western-style jacket nipped in at the waist, with a white shirt and black tie
wang said it follows the style used by most other armies in the world
army officers currently wear olive-green mao suits with red trim
china's military has been acquiring a new look in more ways than one. since 1980, it has trimmed its ranks by 25 percent, to 3 million soldiers, retired scores of aging officers, raised the education requirements for younger officers and increased its use of computers and high-tech weapons
it's a big-city motorist's nightmare: driving aimlessly for an hour or more seeking a legal parking space. many succumb to the temptation of stopping in front of a hydrant or in a ``no parking'' zone
then begins the gamble: will they get caught, and if so, do they pay up?
an associated press check of 13 major u.s. cities showed that they collect at least $380 million annually in parking fines, but many violators ignore the tickets and the backlog of unpaid fines totals more than $1.55 billion in new york and los angeles alone
the amounts the two cities do collect in a year would be enough to finance the budgets of many smaller cities; new york collected an all-time high of $177 million in 1987 and los angeles brought in nearly $59 million
some other large cities are good collectors, too: washington got $38 million last year; chicago, $24 million; san francisco, $28 million; philadelphia, $21.6 million
cities have two purposes in imposing parking fines,'' said john tepper marlin, vice president of the national civic league in new york. ``first, to keep the traffic flowing. second, to collect revenues.''
officials at new york's parking violations bureau don't forgive or forget; they refuse to write off about $1.4 billion in parking penalties dating back eight years. los angeles officials say their city is owed nearly $157 million in parking fines
last month, los angeles mayor tom bradley demonstrated how cities use fines to persuade drivers to improve their parking habits. he announced that fines for illegal parking during rush hours would be nearly doubled, from $28 to $53
bradley said the city expects to collect an additional $6 million in the next year from the higher fines, which are aimed at motorists who clog the right lanes of major streets. he proposed using much of the revenue for improvements, such as building left-hand turn pockets, that would ease congestion
in detroit, under a plan that took effect last week, 52,000 scofflaws with six or more unpaid parking tickets will have to pay their fines or lose their right to update, renew or replace their driver's licenses
payments of parking fines rose from $386,000 in december to $956,000 in january after mayor coleman young announced the plan. city officials estimate that some 60,000 drivers owe $24 million in unpaid parking fines
boston officials said a similar non-renewal system has helped improve its collection percentage of parking fines from 20 percent to between 65 and 75 percent
many cities also nab illegally parked cars with such measures as towing. indianapolis tows some 19,000 cars a year; any car with more than six tickets automatically goes on the towing list
we have a rather aggressive system,'' said william eubanks, who instituted a computerized tracking system 12 years ago when he took charge of city's traffic violations bureau
however, towing cars can backfire. about 15 percent of the cars impounded in grand rapids, mich., are never claimed by their owners
then there's the device known as the denver boot (it was first used there in 1955), which can be locked on the wheel of a scofflaw's parked car, immobilizing it until unpaid fines are cleared up
san antonio, texas, last week joined such cities as los angeles, philadelphia, chicago, washington and pittsburgh that use a boot
kirby thomas, a san antonio attorney, refused to believe his car should have been ``booted.'' the week before, he said, he had paid $63 for six delinquent tickets
however, a check of city records showed that he owned a second car with eight overdue tickets. thomas paid $89 in fines for his second car and $35 to remove the boot from the car he was driving
a month earlier, after a drop in the number of parking tickets issued by police was partly blamed for a city budget crisis, houston began to use the boot to corral cars whose owners had three or more unpaid tickets
on the first day the device was used, 70 drivers were ``booted'' and had to pay $100 just to have the device removed
cities also use the carrot-and-stick technique to encourage scofflaws to pay their fines
chicago collected $5 million last year in an amnesty period that allowed delinquents to pay tickets at half price. in st. paul, minn., where an estimated $2.5 million in parking tickets is owed, an amnesty program last year brought in about $140,000. and miami, owed a similar figure in tickets, offers an annual amnesty period in which it waives late fees for those who pay up
many cities do not know how much they collect or how much they are owed because of divided jurisdictions or because parking statistics are lumped in with other vehicular violations. policies</head>
the democratic presidential candidates want to increase pressure on south africa to force change in that nation, while george bush generally favors pursuing the reagan administration's policies, a survey says
the investor responsibility research center's survey said the democrats _ jesse jackson, michael dukakis and albert gore _ differ dramatically from bush, the likely gop nominee, on what u.s. policy should be toward south africa and the region
the center is a public policy group that tracks issues and investment in south africa, a country where blacks are denied social and political rights through a system known as apartheid
the country's racial segregation has attracted interest in united states, particularly among the black voters who have turned out in force for jackson
jackson's successes in the primaries ensure that the candidates' positions on south africa, mozambique and angola will be scrutinized in 1988
jackson, who is black, has long stressed support for the oppressed in south africa
the survey, which was based on the candidates' statements and a questionnaire, show that vice president bush for the most part endorses the policies the administration has pursued over the last seven years
former television evangelist pat robertson, bush's only rival for the gop nomination, is the sole candidate seeking to repeal the 1986 sanctions that congress slapped on white-ruled south africa. robertson, however, has done poorly in the primaries and is not expected to win the nomination
in contrast to the republicans, the democrats want the united states to pursue a tougher line against south africa
gore, a tennessee senator who portrays himself a moderate, is less extreme than jackson and dukakis, the massachusetts governor. the latter two agree on many points
here is a breakdown of the candidates' positions, according to the survey
jackson and dukakis want additional sanctions against pretoria if south africa does not end its state of emergency, release political prisoners, remove the ban on the african national congress _ the outlawed political organization based in lusaka, zambia _ and enter into negotiations to repeal the apartheid laws
the two also have spoken in favor of u.s. companies pulling out of south africa
gore is more equivocal about more sanctions, saying he would consider them if south africa shows ``no real and dramatic progress.'' he said companies should make their own decisions on disinvestment
bush would not recommend additional sanctions, but he wouldn't repeal those put in place in 1986. the house is considering a sanctions bill that amounts to a total embargo on south africa
bush suggests the ``use of diplomacy and negotiations for constructive change rather than impose additional sanctions.''
the democrats pledge to have routine dialogue with the anc. they also say pretoria should negotiate with the anc and other groups
bush says he would continue the reagan administration's periodic diplomatic contacts with the anc
dukakis and jackson want to stop u.s. aid to the anti-communist unita rebels headed by jonas savimbi, and, if elected, they would extend diplomatic recognition to the soviet-backed angolan government
gore says he is troubled with the aid to the rebels, but that they must be incorporated into a political settlement. he does not promise to recognize the angolan government
bush supports aid to the rebels as a way of blocking soviet encroachment in africa. he would not recognize luanda in an effort to compel the angolans to begin talks with unita and expel 40,000 cuban troops from the country
bush views the cuban troops as the most important obstacle to peace in the region. dukakis and jackson say that a south african pullout from namibia could lead to a cuban withdrawal. south africa maintains their troops in namibia to protect the country from the cubans in angola
bush and the democrats agree with the reagan administration's policy of backing the mozambique government instead of the renamo rebels, who are reportedly aided by south africa
the democrats favor restoration of economic aid to zimbabwe. aid was cut off in mid-1986 after zimbabwean officials insulted former president jimmy carter at a fourth of july party
pope john paul ii made an emotional plea for peace, justice and human rights sunday in an easter message from a rain-soaked balcony overlooking 100,000 people in st. peter's square
after a solemn mass inside st. peter's basilica, attended by u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, the pope wished the world a happy easter in 52 languages
the mass, usually held outdoors on the flower-decked steps of st. peter's, was moved inside christendom's largest church because of rain
john paul then appeared on the church's central balcony, unprotected from the steady drizzle, and addressed an estimated 100,000 people in the square and millions more following by television and radio around the world
at the end of his traditional easter message ``urbi and orbi'' (to the city of rome and the world), the pope departed from his written text and made a special plea to the virgin mary
pray for peace in the world, for justice, pray for the rights of man, especially for religious freedom, for every man, for every christian and non-christian, pray for us,'' john paul said, speaking in italian in a strong, emotional voice
pray for the solidarity of all peoples of the world, the first world, second, third and fourth, all the world,'' he continued. ``in yours and our easter joy, we carry again this weight of humanity, this weight of so many human hearts, our brothers, our sisters, and we repeat: pray for us.''
later, in another impromptu remark, the pope thanked those following on television and radio and urged them to ``pray to mary and with mary for all the people, all the families, all the people who suffer, especially for those countries where peace, justice and the means are lacking.''
earlier in his prepared message, the pope also addressed his words to mary, for whom he has a special devotion and dedicated the current marian year
christ whom you bore is risen, hallelujah,'' said the pope, wearing a white robe trimmed with gold and a tall, gold bishop's hat. ``queen of heaven, rejoice. this is the day of the church's easter joy. we all share in your glory, oh mother.''
after a warm, sun-drenched early spring, winter returned to rome this weekend, with a cold rain drenching the capital sunday morning and dampening the spirits of the hundreds of thousands of tourists visiting the capital for easter
it was decided at the last moment to move the easter sunday mass inside the basilica, where the pope celebrated the service from an altar under the ``baldacchino,'' the immense baroque canopy designed by bernini
shultz, an episcopalian, and his wife helena, a roman catholic, were in the front row of the packed church. mrs. shultz was among those taking communion from the pope
shultz left later in the day for israel on the first part of his new middle east peace shuttle. in a private audience at the vatican on saturday, the pope had given shultz his blessing for the mission
a choir sang byzantine verses in the ancient slavic language paleoslavonic, the first time they had been sung in rome at a papal ceremony since the ninth century
vatican officials said it was meant to show solidarity with christians celebrating the 1,000th anniversary of their faith in what is now the soviet union
the crowd in the square broke into loud cheers and chants of ``viva il papa'' (long live the pope) when john paul, keeping with tradition, appeared on the balcony at noon to deliver his easter message and blessing
afterwards, the polyglot pope offered brief easter greetings in 52 languages ranging from english to ukrainian to swahili
the longest and final greeting was in his native polish, addressed to ``all my fellow countrymen in my country and all around the world and to all those who in the midst of adversity and anxiety are trying to find a path.''
it's a grand wake for those who share the pain of rep. billy tauzin's dashed hopes for the governor's seat _ a cruise into the sunset to retire some of his $1.1 million campaign debt
the six-day outing leaving monday for the mexican resorts of cozumel and cancun is a smaller-scale version of former gov. edwin edwards' 1983 trip to paris and monte carlo
edwards retired a $4 million debt as backers almost tripped over each other to pay $10,000 for the ride. but tauzin said he will net only $250,000 from his trip aboard the canada star, which costs a mere $3,000 to $6,000 a head
it's a chance to be with my people, thank them personally and also do something nice for those who worked with us,'' the congressman said in a telephone interview from the tiny coastal town of chackbay last week
with some wealthy backers paying for tickets they won't use, tauzin said he is doling out their tickets to key people who worked in his 1987 campaign. in all, 250 people will set sail
tauzin also sent letters to lobbyists telling them they would have a captive audience of several congressmen, who were invited along free of charge. he said he approached the house and senate ethics committee about the trip and the cruise organizers ``will follow the (ethics) rules strictly.''
but tauzin said he wasn't sure how many would show up
wayne smith, a political consultant, said about 30 cabins had been sold to washington politicians and businessmen as of last week
the cruise, tauzin said, is no different from staging a cocktail party or dinner at a hotel to raise money to pay off campaign debts
it's a long, extended cocktail party,'' he said
tauzin, along with edwards, lost the governorship last fall to buddy roemer, who remains behind to deal with a debt no junket is likely to retire. the almost bankrupt state owes $2 billion
