the medallions were authorized by the wyoming historical society in the 1950s. thieves also have taken medallions from markers on the mormon trail and the pony express route
this has been happening all over the state because these trails run from border to border,'' said bill mortimer of the bureau of land management ``the longer we leave them out there, the more susceptible they are to vandalism.''
there are still a few marker posts with medallions, but mortimer said he doesn't know where they are
and if i did know, i probably wouldn't tell you,'' he said
the first black chancellor of the university of maryland-college park is resigning to become president of occidental college in california
john b. slaughter, 54, informed the board of regents on friday he is resigning as head of the nation's seventh largest public college campus to take the presidency at the small liberal arts college near los angeles on aug. 1
slaughter became chancellor in november 1982, after serving as head of the national science foundation. he sought to increase recruitment and retention of black students and faculty at the state's 38,000-student flagship campus, and succeeded in boosting black full-time enrollment from about 8 percent in 1983 to 12.5 percent last year
students' average sat scores jumped 50 points during his tenure and the enrollment of foreign students increased 88 percent, a university spokeswoman said
air sickness put a damper on the reunion between an 18-year-old amerasian and the parents she had not seen since she was 2 years old
truong thi thanh thuy, daughter of a little compton man who married a vietnamese wife while in southeast asia, was reunited with her parents friday at new york's kennedy airport
she appeared solemn and neither smiled nor cried, but her parents, bruce and truong mason, later learned that she had been airsick just before the plane landed. she cheered up by the time they reached new england, mason said
in 1972, thuy and her parents were separated when the masons left vietnam and thought thuy would be able to follow on the next flight. but red tape and the fall of saigon to the north vietnamese held up her departure
thuy had been living with her grandparents, uncle, aunt and two cousins, all of whom left vietnam with her
after investigators found four people shot to death at an athens farm and a 70-year-old woman missing last july, the sheriff said, ``you find me helen, and i'll probably tell you what happened.''
last week, investigators found bones in a marsh that they believe are those of the missing helen kunz
and now marathon county sheriff leroy schillinger says it will probably be some time before he can tell the public what happened
no arrests have been made based on the discovery, but taylor county chief deputy sheriff william breneman predicted there would be charges
i'm not sure exactly how soon, but they're coming,'' he said
miss kunz's son kenneth says he arrived home after a night of drinking on july 5 and found his uncle, two aunts and his brother dead, each shot with a .22-caliber weapon. his mother was missing
there was no reason for them to do this to my family,'' kenneth kunz said last week after the discovery of the remains believed to be his mother. ``i hope they find who done it.''
investigators ruled out robbery as a motive after they found about $1,000 in the home
neighbors knew little about the family that lived on a 108-acre farm in a wooden house off a dirt road in central wisconsin. the family rarely invited people into the cluttered house but did most of their business at the door, neighbors said. kenneth kunz, 55, lived in a trailer next to the house
the house had a wood stove and no indoor plumbing. but merchants said helen kunz had bought a videocassette recorder and microwave oven for the family
hardware store owner gale weiler said the woman also bought .22-caliber ammunition a few weeks before the killings and complained that her family watched ``dirty movies'' on the vcr. she said the ammunition was for her younger son, 30-year-old randy kunz, to shoot birds
you find me helen and i'll probably tell you what happened,'' schillinger said just after the killings
miss kunz, who never married, was described by people in town as the family matriarch who paid the bills and did laundry while randy waited in the car. randy also accompanied her to high school sports games
miss kunz's sisters, irene, 81, and marie, 72, were seen less frequently by neighbors, who remembered the women working in their garden and wearing old-fashioned clothes. their brother, clarence, 76, had been ill and had retired from farming
as investigators probed the family's past, questions of incest, which first arose during a 1930s rape trial, resurfaced and have yet to be solved
lawyers raised the possibility of incest during the trial of a 40-year- old neighbor whom helen kunz, then 15 and pregnant, had accused of attacking her. her mother denied the incest accusations and the neighbor was convicted in 1933 of statutory rape
kenneth kunz told the milwaukee sentinel in an interview after the killings that he thought clarence kunz was his father
authorities based their identification of the remains found last week on clothing _ ``some tattered, some scattered, some with'' skeletal remains _ found in the marsh about 16 miles north of the kunz farm, lt. elwood mason said
the bones and clothing were taken to the state crime laboratory in madison for forensic tests, expected to take several days
around six months after the killings, police questioned several people and held a 21-year-old man in jail over a weekend for interrogation. but they released him without charges and no one else was arrested
in mid-march, investigators gathered reporters from as far away as minneapolis and milwaukee and escorted them to a manure pit, where authorities dug for three days without finding any evidence
police said a detective found the remains last week on the basis of information from an informant whom they would not identify
mason and schillinger said there are more than one but fewer than a dozen suspects in the case, but would not say if the discovery of the remains eliminated any suspects or drew their focus to anyone in particular
i don't think it adds any new questions,'' said mason, who has been heading the investigation. ``we may have eliminated some. you don't know.''
thousands of roman catholics marched peacefully in northern ireland on sunday to commemorate the 1916 easter rising against british rule in what is now the republic of ireland
police abandoned a short-lived policy of staying away from funerals and other occasions organized by sympathizers of the outlawed irish republican army and mounted heavy patrols around the main march through the catholic ghettos of west belfast
armored land rovers, with officers riding shotgun, drove at the head and tail of the mile-long procession. about 5,000 people, waving irish tricolor flags, marched to the sound of pipe bands to the catholic milltown cemetery
police reported no incidents at the parades in belfast, londonderry, the second largest city, and 10 smaller centers across protestant-dominated northern ireland
british troops, with rifles cocked, also patrolled the west belfast route, lined by catholics wearing orange, green and white badges, the tricolor colors, embossed with a lily
the flower is the symbol of the 1916 uprising in dublin. the uprising led to independence six years later for the overwhelmingly catholic republic
britain, at the insistence of protestants in the north, retained control of the six northern counties, which now make up northern ireland
the easter sunday parades marked the start of the annual marching season in northern ireland where protestants and catholics separately commemorate key dates of their troubled history
protestant marches were due to begin monday
in milltown cemetery, where a protestant gunman killed three people in a march 16 attack on an unpoliced ira funeral, police ringed marchers as they thronged round a memorial to guerrillas killed in the ira's bomb-and-bullet campaign to end british rule
we have a message for the british government,'' said martin mcguinness, vice president of sinn fein, the ira's legal political wing
we will demoralize you. we will make your six counties into a millstone which will strangle you.''
police stared silently as the crowd burst into applause when mcguinness declared:
our strategy ... is to sap the political will of the british government and the british people to remain in ireland. the means are limited guerrilla warfare against the crown forces.''
the royal ulster constabulary ended its no-policing policy after an upsurge of sectarian violence last month culminated in the murder of two british soldiers who drove into an ira funeral march 19
sunday's march passed close to the spot where the two signals corpsmen, in plainclothes, were dragged from their car by the funeral mob, beaten and then shot by ira gunmen
the spate of killings, in which 12 people died, began march 6 when british commandos fatally shot three unarmed ira guerrillas who were on a bombing mission in the british colony of gibraltar
a total of 2,638 people have been killed since sectarian violence erupted in 1969
mcguinness denied published reports that the ira is considering abandoning violence
the ira position has been on the record for years,'' he told reporters. ``they have stated there will be no more cease-fires.'' save money</head>
liberals and conservatives, often at loggerheads on social programs, are in rare agreement on expanding eight children's programs, citing independent research that shows the programs work well and save the government money
a report released this weekend by the house select committee on children, youth and families cites specific costs and benefits of each program as determined by independent research and analysis
the findings have convinced liberals and conservatives that they can be both compassionate and cost-conscious, said rep. dan coates, r-ind., the senior republican on the committee
we're working toward a consensus here,'' coates said. ``i've seen a decided change in attitude ... on the republican side about how we should approach the process of spending.''
whereas there was wholesale ``spare-no-program'' cutting in the early years of the reagan presidency, coates said, members are more discriminating now and willing to spend money on programs that work
absent these standards, you don't get new money,'' said rep. george miller, d-calif., chairman of the children's committee and a member of the house budget committee
miller said the house budget resolution provides several hundred million dollars in increases above inflation for the eight education, health, nutrition and employment programs
the report released this weekend is an update of a 1985 report and contains 25 additional studies that reinforce the original findings
this update gives more credence to the initial effort. it can serve as a very important guideline to the new administration,'' coates said
the report discusses research findings by universities, government agencies and other sources in the areas of medicaid; supplemental nutrition for pregnant women, infants and children (wic); youth employment; preschool education; compensatory education; handicapped education; prenatal care; and immunizations
miller said the report and the update were prompted by the skeptical ``prove-it'' reaction encountered by advocates when they argued that short-term investments would produce long-term savings
he said the initial compilation was instrumental in persuading lawmakers to stop cutting those programs and led to increased spending on them in subsequent years
the key is to back it up with research,'' coates said
the largest child-program increases in the house budget resolution _ a non-binding spending blueprint _ include $210 million for the compensatory education program for children at academic risk and $170 million for handicapped education. other substantial hikes would go to the wic program ($150 million) and head start ($77 million)
among the newer findings cited in the report:
_national math and reading rankings of students in the compensatory education program increased in every grade except 12th
_it costs only $500 to provide a year of compensatory education to a student at risk of academic failure while it costs more than $3,000 for a student to repeat a grade
_a pregnant woman not participating in wic increased her chances of having a low-birthweight, high-risk baby by 60 percent in one north carolina county
_for every $1 spent on wic in missouri, about 49 cents was saved
_the incidence of nutritional anemia virtually disappeared at an inner city health center from 1971 to 1984; the researcher said 95 percent enrollment in wic probably was the reason
_for every dollar spent on childhood immunization, the government saves $10 in medical costs
for 10 months paroled rapist-mutilator lawrence singleton has lived a hermitlike existence in a trailer at the state prison, the only place authorities could find for him after he was driven out of town after town
on april 25, his parole _ and his stay at san quentin _ will come to an end. singleton will be able to walk away a free man, under no obligation to tell officials where he will settle
the 60-year-old ex-convict bears little resemblance to the burly, hard-drinking ex-sailor convicted of raping and sodomizing 15-year-old hitchhiker mary vincent in 1978 and chopping off her forearms with an ax
today, he lives on a small social security grant and spends his days tending the yard around his trailer in a remote corner of the 1,000-acre prison grounds
although not formally under guard, he observes a 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew and is watched by at least one parole officer when he leaves the grounds for weekly visits to a psychologist, officials said
when he wants to go shopping, he asks us because he has no transportation,'' said ronald chun, regional parole administrator for the department of corrections. ``technically, we have him under surveillance. he can walk around on his own, but for all practical purposes we are escorting him.''
if it weren't for the press calls, we wouldn't know he was out there,'' said prison spokesman dave langerman. ``out of sight is out of mind. anyone out on the streets has more to fear from the unknown _ the guy with the tattoo next to them in the supermarket _ than from this poor little burned-out guy under escort.''
singleton does not grant interviews, but has had occasional visitors, including ex-wife mary collins, a retired nurse who offered him a home but was refused by parole authorities, said michael van winkle, a corrections spokesman
singleton served nine years, 11 months of a 14-year, four-month sentence in the california men's colony at san luis obispo, receiving an early release for good behavior and through a work-credit program, chun said
the early release infuriated residents of a half-dozen small communities where authorities tried to place singleton last spring. in rodeo, about 25 miles northeast of san francisco, a mob of 500 people forced officers to move singleton under armed guard from a hotel room
finally, in june, gov. george deukmejian ordered singleton placed at san quentin for the duration of his one-year parole
once his parole ends, singleton is under no obligation to tell officials whether he will settle in florida, near relatives, or elsewhere, chun said
i hope he goes to florida. the victim and her parents will feel much better knowing he is gone,'' said nancy fahden, a contra costa county supervisor who fought singleton's release to her county
vincent, who now has a child, declined to be interviewed but said last year, before singleton was paroled, that she still fears her attacker
as a condition of his parole, singleton takes a drug that would make him extremely ill from any amount of alcohol, even if splashed on in an aftershave lotion, langerman said
he is completely, absolutely defused as a threat to society,'' the spokesman said. ``if he takes a drink, he will fall down retching, so you don't have to worry about him going on a bender and going out looking for a hitchhiker.''
but once singleton's parole ends, he is not required to continue the drug, called disulfiram, chun said
yes, there is a concern. he claims he doesn't really need it. he doesn't lose that much control, according to him,'' chun said. singleton maintains, as he did at his trial, that he is innocent and was mistaken for another man
i think, if anything, he's worse now,'' said donald stahl, the stanislaus county prosecutor at singleton's trial
he has not taken responsibility,'' stahl said. ``he lives in a bizarre fantasy land and acquits himself each day. he doesn't accept his guilt and resolve never to do it again.''
a 10-year-old fifth grader is asking new yorkers for quarters to help him become a doctor and find a cure for the diabetes that killed his grandmother and is sapping the health of his grandfather
tony brack sent $10 and this handwritten letter to the new york daily news:
dear sir,
can you please print this for me. i hope this $10 will help the cost for 1 or 2 days in your newspaper
help
i am 10 years old and want to go to college when i grow up. my grandma died 3 weeks ago from diabetes at 56 years young. i want to find a cure for diabetes as my other grandpa has it to. please send a 25 (cents) and it will grow in the bank until then. thank you
tony brack
box 191
oxford, iowa 52322''
the $10 was not enough to cover the cost of a new york daily news advertisement, but tony got his picture and a story about his plea on page two of sunday's daily news
tony was extraordinarily close to his grandmother, joyce brack, said his mother, dianna brack
since both his parents work, tony went to his grandmother's house, about four blocks from home, every day after school
the elder mrs. brack, 56, had undergone the amputation of one leg in january and her eyesight was failing, but she seemed to be doing well under the circumstances, the family said
she died feb. 1, just hours after having dinner with tony's family
a couple of weeks later, tony decided something must be done about diabetes and that he could be the one to do it
the idea of making a public request for funds came from the syndicated newspaper column of bob greene, who wrote about a college student who gathered thousands of dollars by asking for one penny from every person who read greene's column
he's very serious about becoming a doctor and doing something about diabetes,'' his mother said. ``he's a nice, sensitive kid who thinks about people other than himself.''
tony told the daily news: ``i want to go to the university of iowa and train to be a doctor. then i can help stop these bad things happening.''
a senior iranian official said sunday that iran would retaliate for iraq's renewed attacks on iranian cities by launching new ground offensives
iran also revealed that a month of iraqi air and missile attacks on iranian cities has left 1,145 people dead and another 4,000 wounded
deputy foreign minister mohammad javad larijani said any suggestion that the ``war of the cities'' could change the military balance is ``a joke.''
they sent more than 100 missiles into tehran and that could not change anything,'' he added. by iraqi count, 105 missiles have been fired into the iranian capital
larijani said an iraqi raid on the northeastern city of tabriz 330 miles northwest of tehran killed at least 10 civilians and wounded 15 others on sunday
iran's official news media earlier had reported the warplane raid, as well as another air attack on the central city of isfahan
the raids followed a 2{-day lull in iraqi attacks on iranian cities during a visit to baghdad by turkish prime minister turgut ozal. iran also had largely ceased its attacks on iraqi cities
asked whether iran would retaliate for the new raids, larijani said: ``we will have plenty of surprises for them,'' but made it plain that these would come chiefly in the battlefield through ``punitive offensives.''
these offensives will stop them definitely, and they will pay a high price,'' he told a news conference attended by the associated press
iran periodically allows western reporters to travel to tehran
he also said iran has ``anything that is needed'' to prevent the iraqis from using chemical weapons against iranian cities. he did not elaborate
for just over a month iraq has been pounding the iranian capital with al hussein missiles, which it says were made in iraq
western analysts say they are soviet-made scud-bs with boosters to give them extra range to travel the 290 miles to tehran
larijani, who is a deputy foreign minister for economic and international relations, is to meet on wednesday with u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar as part of international efforts to end the 7{-year-old war
he said iran would continue these discussions in a ``cooperative mood'' but reiterated iran's demand for a condemnation of iraq as the aggressor in the war
we are insisting that baghdad be held accountable for ... a long list of criminal actions,'' he said. ``we are going to ask for every bit of our rights.''
in an earlier meeting with western reporters, kamal kharrazi, director-general of iran's war information headquarters, said said iran's val-fajr-10 offensive in mountainous northeastern iraq had achieved its objectives and ended after winning control of about 390 square miles of iraqi territory
a western diplomatic source said he understood that the iraqis had began a counteroffensive with the aim of recapturing the town of halabja
iraqi reportedly attacked halabja with chemical weapons after iran took it in march
a visit to the halabja area for western newsmen, which had been scheduled for monday, was put off without explanation. no new date was given
iran claims 5,000 kurds were killed and another 5,000 injured in the chemical attacks march 16-17. iraq has repeatedly denied using chemical weapons, but also has stressed it is ready to use any weapons at its disposal to defend iraqi soil
president reagan and his wife nancy spent a quiet easter sunday at their secluded ranch in the santa ynez mountains
with with warm temperatures and cloudless skies, reagan attended to chores at rancho del cielo, the first couple's 688-acre property about 30 miles from this seaside resort city
reagan, according to the white house press office, was chopping wood and clearing brush, and then he and the first lady planned a quiet dinner
in contrast to easter sunday a year ago, the reagans did not venture from the ranch to attend worship services, nor was there any gathering of relatives at the ranch this time around
the press office said that in addition to working on the ranch grounds, reagan took care of routine paperwork
the president and his wife will travel to coto de caza in orange county, calif., monday to attend a reception and luncheon for the reagan library foundation
the reagans arrived in california on friday and will vacation until april 10, when they return to the white house. details of post report. picks up 18th graf, `in peshawar .. .'</note>
anti-communist afghan rebel leaders say the united states has stopped supplying stinger anti-aircraft missiles to the guerrillas in apparent anticipation of a settlement of the afghan civil war
soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze, arriving sunday in kabul to confer with afghan government leaders, said the united states and pakistan were blocking talks in geneva aimed at ending the eight-year war
mohamad nabi mohamadi, leader of the harekat islami, one of the seven guerrilla groups fighting communist forces in afghanistan, said the rebels have not been receiving the shoulder-launched missiles for the last four or five months
we are extremely worried,'' nabi mohamadi told the associated press in a weekend interview at his headquarters in the pakistani border city of peshawar
we don't trust the russians. we are afraid because they are deceitful and sly,'' he said, referring to soviet claims that they want to withdraw their estimated 115,000 troops from afghanistan
however, two other guerrilla leaders said the supply of stingers had not stopped
the official soviet tass news agency said in a commentary that peace could be brought to afghanistan without u.s. agreement on a plan to settle the war
the commentary indicates that the kremlin may be willing to sign a settlement in geneva without american assurances that it will stop shipping weapons to afghan rebels
the united states has said it will halt military aid to the rebels only when the soviets stop aiding the communist government in kabul
soviet officials contend that economic and military assistance to the afghanistan government is a bilateral matter outside the scope of the geneva peace talks
shevardnadze told tass that his discussions with afghan president najib would center on the problems delaying an end to the war
unfortunately, serious difficulties have developed at these talks because of the non-constructive position taken by pakistan and the united states,'' the 60-year-old foreign minister said, according to tass
in geneva, the u.n. talks recessed thursday for the easter holiday and were to resume monday. pakistan represents the rebels in the talks
soviet officials had placed high hopes on getting a peace agreement out of the current round of negotiations that began march 2. but the talks have stalled over the question of foreign military assistance to the two sides
soviet troops entered afghanistan in december 1979 to help the communist government battle the insurgents. western analysts say at least 10,000 soviet soldiers have been killed in afghanistan and more than 20,000 wounded
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev offered in february to begin the pullout on may 15 if the settlement plan was signed by march 15. that informal deadline was surpassed when new issues arose at the geneva talks
the washington post reported last week that the u.s. government intended to stop supplying the rebels with stingers, which are said to have dramatically improved the guerrilla's air defenses since they first acquired the deadly missiles in late 1986
the newspaper, quoting unidentified diplomatic sources, said reagan administration was nervous about leaving a large number of the missiles in the hands of afghan factions that cannot be controlled after u.s. ties are cut. some of the missiles have made their way to iran
in peshawar, nabi mohamadi said he assumed the united states stopped the missile shipment because of the possible soviet withdrawal. he said he believed the supplies would resume if the soviets failed to leave afghanistan
but sebghatollah mojadeddi, head of the afghan national liberation front, which is considered moderate, said no halt had been confirmed
the united states has promised that it will not leave us alone and as long as the russians help the kabul government, they will continue helping us,'' mojaddedi said in an interview
ahmad gilani, leader of the national islamic front of afghanistan, said, ``i know that they have not halted the stingers.''
ahmad shah, whom the guerrillas have chosen to head a rebel interim government in afghanistan if the soviets leave, said the halt in the stingers would not deter the guerrillas from battling the communists
we never asked for stingers,'' he said. ``this was their decision. when we didn't have the stingers, we (still) were fighting and shooting down enemy planes.''
yunis khalis, leader of the hezbi islami rebel group, declined to confirm that the supply of stingers had been halted. but he charged the americans were helping the rebels only to serve their own interests
we never stretched our hands out to america for military help,'' khalis said
khalis said that even without u.s. aid the rebels ``will continue their battle.''
a soviet customs inspector became suspicious of an african couple because of their roundabout travel route and found $10 million worth of heroin packed inside their suitcases, a newspaper said sunday
police arrested the couple, from cotonou, benin, after the incident at moscow's sheremetyevo airport, komsomolskaya pravda reported
the newspaper did not say when the alleged smuggling attempt occurred or whether the pair had been formally charged
it said more than 32 pounds of heroin was found in five suitcases carried by the couple. komsomolskaya pravda said the drugs would have a black market value of about $10 million
customs inspector vyacheslav chugunov was credited by the newspaper with discovering the narcotics
chugunov told the newspaper he became suspicious of the couple when he noticed they were passing through moscow on a trip home from new delhi, which he said was far from the shortest or simplest route
in recent years, there have been several cases of foreigners arrested for attempting to smuggle drugs through sheremetyevo airport. they generally believe that arrival from moscow attracts less attention from customs agents at their final destination
after high-stepping past allegations of cruelty and abuse for over three decades, the tennessee walking horse industry may be stopped in its tracks by a federal court ruling, officials say
based on the decision of a washington district judge, the u.s. department of agriculture banned the stacked shoes and limited the weight of leg chains used to give the show horses their flamboyant stride
the move has crippled the walking horse industry, said mack motes, president of the walking horse trainers association, which plans to help fight the court decision
we're trying to save our breed,'' motes said
several shows in alabama and tennessee have been canceled since the regulations were announced two weeks ago, and things look grim for the tennessee walking horse national celebration. the annual 10-day show, scheduled for late this summer in shelbyville, typically attracts more than 2,000 horses from across the country and is considered the world series of the breed
i don't think the celebration could go this year,'' said frederick harper, an animal scientist with the university of tennessee agricultural extension service
u.s. district judge oliver gasch ordered the new regulations in a suit filed by the american horse protection association against the agriculture department
the rules forbid the use of bracelet-like chains weighing more than 6 ounces and padded shoes for racking and walking horses. chains of up to 10 ounces and stacked shoes 4 inches high had been allowed
the special shoes and chains are needed to keep the walking horse industry on its feet, proponents say
a horse on stacked shoes ``gives a better show .... that old horse really gets into it,'' said reese smith jr., spokesman of friends of the show horse
but animal protection activists say chains can cause soreness and swelling of the leg and that padded shoes, which cover the horses' hooves, help hide sores. they also can hide objects that are placed between the horses' hooves and the shoes to cause the animals pain, said russ gaspar, general counsel for the american horse protection association
many in the industry say they are being penalized for abuses long since corrected, including the use of chemical irritants in the 1960s
irritants placed above the hoof combined with chains to make horses lift their feet up and out in a flamboyant gait called the ``big lick,'' but they also gave the animals raw sores
their widespread use helped push congress to pass the horse protection act of 1970, which banned irritants and other soring practices and prompted the industry to form an elaborate inspection system for each show
motes said the industry isn't causing sores now and added that 98 percent of horses inspected over the past five years have passed
nevertheless, the judge ruled that horse protection group had raised doubts about the accuracy of show inspections in the suit
usda spokeswoman nancy robinson said the department on friday asked gasch whether the industry could keep using the devices while the department sets final rules, which could take two months or more
smith, whose organization has raised over $400,000 and hired lawyers to fight the court decision, said industry groups do not know yet exactly how they will fight the decision, but they expect to challenge it in court
harper estimates the state's economy would lose about $140 million in one year if walking horse shows were wiped out. there are about 500 shows in the state each year, mostly to benefit charities, he said
the walking horse is the only show horse that really attracts people, they're exciting,'' smith said. ``we have a special horse. and we're treated special _ especially bad.''
a diesel oil spill disappeared sunday from the ohio river as mysteriously as it had appeared, a u.s. coast guard spokesman said
we can't find a trace of it,'' said lt. eric mosher, who was part of a team that conducted a land search along a 50-mile stretch of the river from louisville to madison, ind., where the slick was spotted saturday
mosher said the oil seen the previous day was light and tends to evaporate
the search team checked out banks on both sides of the river and ``nothing was found. we still don't know where the slick originated,'' mosher said
barges, towboats and holding tanks had been checked but provided no clues, he said
jerry ford, a spokesman for the louisville water co., said powdered activated carbon was added to the treatment process as a precaution but that no problems were expected with the water supply
madison draws its water from underground streams and was not affected
sgt. carroll henneke of the indiana department of natural resources said, ``we've had no fish kill and haven't observed loss of any marine life.''
madison police alerted the coast guard to the spill about 7 a.m. saturday after receiving a report of a strong diesel smell in the river friday evening
initially, there were reports that the spill extended upstream from madison, but mosher said workers at markland lock and dam about 20 miles upstream from madison and at mcalpine lock and dam in louisville were unable to see or smell it
michael dukakis says he will criticize fellow democratic hopeful jesse jackson on occasion, but refrained from doing so on sunday. he also said no one knows whether jackson is could win against vice president george bush
dukakis argued that the voters are not interested in fellow democrat albert gore jr.'s criticisms of himself and jackson, and rejected suggestions that criticism of jackson would help indicate what his own values are
why is that a test of one's presidential qualities?'' he asked reporters outside of st. constantine church here
i disagree with jesse jackson...and i have expressed those disagreements and will in the future. but i don't think the american people have the slightest interest in what al gore thinks of him or of me,'' dukakis added
gore, a tennessee senator, criticized jackson sharply last week on foreign policy and experience. dukakis hesitated to do the same, but said there are several areas in which he and jackson have policy disagreements
the massachusetts governor visited three churches on easter sunday, before picking up his campaigning for votes in tuesday's wisconsin primary
he dropped in on services at an all-black church and served fish and fries at a sunday supper. he also attended services at annuciation greek orthodox church, which was celebrating palm sunday under his church's calendar. then dukakis flew to a farm in northern wisconsin before wrapping up his day in madison
the democratic hopeful was pressed on his judgment of jackson's electability, a matter of concern to many democratic leaders. the two men are locked in a tight race in wisconsin
asked if either he or jackson could beat bush, he answered: ``yes, but i think i have best chance of doing so...i think george bush is beatable. i'd like to be able to run against him.''
then dukakis was asked if he disagrees with democrats who say jackson is unelectable in november
i don't think there is any way of telling, based on what we have seen over the past year...there are no sure things,'' dukakis said
asked about the subject again later, he said, ``i make no predictions.''
i do think i'm the strongest candidate against bush. i think i can take the fight to him. i think i can build a very broad coalition with people... who want somebody who has the skill and the ability and the experience to do this job, who has balanced budgets...who has a record. that's my strength in this race
in the last analysis, what we want is a victory,'' he added
dukakis is leading in the latest polls in wisconsin, but he said that is meaningless
i don't pay attention to polls. there were all kinds of polls in michigan that said i was ahead. it's on tuesday that the people of this state will decide who will be the strongest nominee and best president,'' he said
jackson beat dukakis 2-1 in the michigan caucuses on march 26 after dukakis was leading in the polls there
dukakis said he was going to continue to emphasize his positive message and avoid attacks on other candidates unless he is first attacked. he said that approach is working for both him and jackson
i think it is significant that the two of us who are positive and hopeful and optimistic about this country are also leading in this race,'' dukakis said
dukakis mentioned three disagreements with jackson: middle east policy, oil import fees and how to provide health insurance for all americans
secretary of state george p. shultz, launching a fresh u.s. peace venture, told israel sunday night to act on his plan for negotiations for palestinian self-rule
negotiations work,'' he said in a strong arrival statement. ``the time to act on it is now.''
shultz said the palestinians must be included in the talks and negotiations must be based on a 1967 united nations resolution that calls on israel to give up territory in exchange for arab recognition
shultz acknowledged that the plan he presented last month to arab and israeli leaders on a swing through the region was difficult for everyone
but he said that ``the balance in our approach is evident'' and that picking on objectionable parts ``is to take a road labeled delay and frustration.''
his message was intended for israel's prime minister yitzhak shamir, who on a trip to washington in mid-march condemned shultz's call for an international peace conference
shultz, quoting from ecclesiastes, said there is ``a time of war and time of peace.''
he said: ``this is the time and the season to move decisively towards peace.''
the conference would be held this month as a way of launching negotiations on may 1 to provide some self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs on the west bank and in gaza
but shamir objected that it could provide an active and meddlesome role for the soviet union, who usually back arab positions and broke diplomatic relations with israel 21 years ago
on a tour of the troubled west bank, shamir again took a stiff stand sunday. he said he expected no breakthrough in his talks with shultz that begin monday
he again dismissed the conference proposal, saying shultz should explain to him why direct talks are not possible without such a multi-party meeting
israel would deal in the negotiations with a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation to work out a three-year interim arrangement for the occupied areas. meanwhile, negotiations on the overall settlement of the arab-israeli conflict would begin in december
foreign minister shimon peres, who favors the approach, greeted shultz and his wife enthusiastically at the ben gurion international airport near tel aviv
adressing them as ``george and helena,'' peres invited them to join in this passover season in prayers for peace
we shall pray, knowing there is no easy way to peace. the obstacles are so many and the light so dim,'' peres said. but he said, ``it is our duty to provide a green light.''
peres said israel was still looking for palestinians to agree to enter the process
stones are not messages and messages do not need the threat of stones,'' he said, referring to the four months of anti-israeli protests which have claimed the lives of 136 palestinians and one israeli soldier
mark spreyer doesn't mind when people say his job is for the birds. even his business cards read: ``mark spreyer, the naturalist nobody likes, defending the species nobody wants. starlings my speciality.''
spreyer never meant to become an advocate for one of the nation's least-liked birds, but the 31-year-old ornithologist for the chicago academy of sciences thinks they're getting a bad rap as messy invaders who take over other birds' turf
he recently delivered a lecture titled ``in defense of starlings'' before the national wildlife rehabilitators association in denver, and he has also spoken on the birds' behalf in new york and orlando, fla
he even has one for a pet. rod starling shares spreyer's suburban barrington apartment, has learned to talk and has been known to fly to the telephone when it rings and get the receiver off the hook
some of spreyer's enthusiasm has caught on, according to a local veterinarian, peregrine wolff, interviewed by the chicago sun-times recently after encountering spreyer's pet
my opinion of starlings was not very high before i met this bird,'' said ms. wolff, who said rod imitated spreyer's telephone bell and answering-machine beep, and then in a hitchcockian twist, said clearly, ``this is mark spreyer.''
starlings are related to talking myna birds, and spreyer said sunday their talent as mimics helped them wing their way into his heart. ``i'm embarrassed to admit it now, but eight years ago, i used to consider them as owl food,'' said spreyer
spreyer became better acquainted with starlings two years ago while preparing for a lecture on urban wildlife, which includes other european imports such as house sparrows and pigeons
people are trained to think all introduced things are bad and all native things are good,'' spreyer said sunday. ``i've come to realize that we have to deal with the environment as it is today.''
starlings, which often gather in large, noisy flocks, have gotten an undeservedly bad reputation as mess-makers and nuisances, while their good points are overlooked, he said
the black songbirds use a completely different food source than other birds, he said
while most birds have strong squeezing muscles in their beaks to enable them to crack nuts, for example, starlings have mighty muscles for prying things open, adapting them perfectly for digging up cutworms and other pests
groundskeepers at some golf courses welcome starlings, which reduce the need for pesticides, spreyer said
there are plenty of other birds that make a mess,'' and the starling's reputation for displacing native birds with aggressive nesting habits is overblown, he said
some critics remain unconvinced, including ron ogden, illinois director of animal-damage control for the u.s. department of agriculture
they've gotten a bad rap because they're bad birds,'' he told the sun-times. ``i can't believe anybody would be talking up starlings after all the damage they've caused. ... i know mark, i like him, but he doesn't have to deal with them every day like i do. they give me fits.''
ogden said crews have been pruning trees around the old state capitol in springfield to evict non-native starlings whose droppings made a ``teetotal mess.''
democrat jesse jackson preached easter sermons to huge white, black and hispanic crowds sunday, invoking the memory of martin luther king jr. and declaring, ``hope has been unleashed.''
there is a sense of hope and renewal in the air,'' jackson told a largely hispanic catholic congregation where hundreds stood outside. ``not an easter of eggs and rabbits and ruffled dresses, but an easter of authentic hope and renewal _ shaking of shackles.''
jackson repeatedly referred to the crucifixion of jesus christ and compared his death to that of king, the civil rights leader slain 20 years ago monday in memphis
dr. king and jesus ... government set the climates for their killings,'' he said. ``... dr. king got in trouble with our government for ending apartheid.''
he compared the crucifixion as well to the suffering of the poor, and used the symbolism of easter and the resurrection in describing the end of president reagan's administration
the real easter is going on,'' jackson said. ``... we survived seven years of midnight.''
jackson was campaigning a second day in colorado, where democrats express a choice for president in statewide caucuses monday night that will apportion 45 delegates
as jackson was met with large, enthusiastic crowds, his campaign manager, california assembly speaker willie brown, said in a tv interview that the jackson forces are ready for the closer scrutiny that comes with a candidate's emergence as a frontrunner
what jesse jackson has done during the course of the last four or five months ... people have not paid close attention to him, have not asked him whole lots of questions _ he's been in a position where he is really prepared his answers. he's prepared himself to respond to any questions put to him,'' brown said on the abc-tv ``this week with david brinkley'' program
jackson is smart. he has observed, and he is ready to be looked at really closely, far more closely than he has been looked at in the past.''
brown also said that ``there is a new jackson,'' who has shown `'phenomenal growth'' since his 1984 campaign
jackson on sunday spoke at denver's predominantly white first baptist church, where a joint service was held with the predominantly black shorter african methodist episcopal church. some 1,500 people crowded the church and watched on television from the basement, and at least as many stood outside in the warm sun, listening on loudspeakers
he then went to our lady of guadalupe catholic church in a predominantly hispanic, working class neighborhood. the church was jammed and hundreds lined up for a block - a half-dozen deep - to catch a glimpse of the candidate
denver mayor federico pena sat with jackson at the catholic church
why are so many people here today?'' jackson asked the congregation. ``because hope has been let loose.''
jackson was met with similarly large and enthusiastic crowds saturday in three other colorado cities, including the affluent ski resort aspen
i sense, as i travel around the nation, something is going on,'' he said at first baptist church. ``there are several thousand people outdoors. something is going on. ... from aspen to alabama, something is going on.''
sitting in the front row was gary hart, the former colorado senator who dropped out of the presidential race, accompanied by his wife lee and daughter andrea
neither hart nor pena has endorsed jackson. reading one of the old testament lessons at the first church was the state democratic party chairman buie seawell, who is backing michael dukakis against jackson for the democratic presidential nomination
jackson delivered sermons heavy with biblical references, but blended with it political references to himself and criticism of president reagan. the congregations responded with shouts and applause
one of his standard political lines got applause at the catholic church
i would rather have roosevelt in a wheelchair than reagan on a horse,'' he said
rep. samuel stratton says he's endorsing gov. mario cuomo for president, despite cuomo's insistence that he's not a candidate
the only really outstanding candidate that's going to help the democratic party is mario cuomo and the sooner he recognizes that, and the democratic party recognizes that, we're headed for victory,'' the veteran albany-area congressman said
stratton said in a weekend radio interview he would back the bid of former westchester county congressman richard ottinger, who's urging voters in new york's april 19 democratic primary to vote for an uncommitted slate with the hope cuomo will change his mind
he said he knows a ``fantastic number of people in the albany area who want to see him as a presidential candidate.''
with his entry into the race we would have a very exciting finish,'' said stratton
he said he had little hope for the democratic party if no one else emerges besides frontrunners michael dukakis and jesse jackson
if that's all it's going to be, we might as well throw the race,'' he said
wisconsin's republican members of congress say vice president george bush will fare exceptionally well in november's general election simply because the democrats feel he is the weakest candidate
he will do better than people expect. he will be stronger and more tenacious,'' said rep. steve gunderson, who shifted his support from sen. bob dole, of kansas, to bush after dole dropped out of the gop race
rep. toby roth, who has not endorsed anyone in wisconsin's presidential primary tuesday, agreed with gunderson that the democrats' perception of bush will be advantageous
remember 1980. all the democrats were saying they hoped the republicans would nominate ronald reagan _ he'd be the easiest to beat,'' roth said. ``so we nominated reagan and the democrats didn't even come within striking distance.''
roth said the continuation of a sound economy, low interest rates and lack of american involvement in ``shooting war'' would help bush win the general election
rep. thomas petri said bush's ability to differentiate himself from reagan policy and speak out ``more clearly on domestic issues so he can use the election as a mandate for policy change'' will be the key to a bush victory
times have changed and so the emphasis and the issues must change. he must differentiate himself from reagan,'' said petri, who endorsed bush's candidacy nearly a year ago
cardinal miguel obando y bravo prayed sunday during the easter mass for a definitive truce in the 6{-year-old civil war and a ``passage from war to life.''
the roman catholic prelate also announced, after speaking with representatives of the government and rebels, that peace talks scheduled to open wednesday in managua had been postponed until april 12
a 60-day cease-fire signed march 23 went into effect friday and the defense ministry said sunday there were no reports of violations
the rebels' nicaraguan resistance alliance on saturday insisted the meeting set for wednesday be postponed for a week, saying technical talks to work out the mechanics for the cease-fire had net been resolved
obando y bravo, who is an observer at the peace negotiations, told the nearly 300 people who attended mass at the small las sierritas church that the one-week delay of the talks is ``sad for our people.''
he told the worshipers the new round of peace talks had been delayed because the rebels, known as contras, said the sandinista government had not complied with the plan signed by both sides at meetings last month in the border outpost of sapoa
but the cardinal said he is satisfied with the progress in the negotiations and ``i have a lot of hope on this easter sunday.''
enough of death, a step toward life,'' he said as members of the congregation applauded and cheered
military officers from the government and nicaraguan resistance met march 28-29 in sapoa and agreed to set up five zones in which the contra combatants would gather as part of the truce
they did not, however, establish in detail the zones or security measure for the rebels
contra leader adolfo calero said saturday night in a telephone interview from miami: ``we are living up to the accord. however the reason we asked for a delay in the talks is that the zones have yet to be established and there are many details.''
the rebels also said the sandinistas had not freed all the prisoners requested by the contras when the government released 100 political prisoners march 29. the cease-fire plan calls for the gradual release of 3,300 political prisoners
in another complaint, the contras said the government had violated the provision of the plan that provides for unrestricted freedom of expression by withholding newsprint to the opposition newspaper la prensa. newsprint, like other imported items, is in short supply
la prensa, in its march 26 edition, said it would not publish during holy week
pro-government newspapers also haven't published papers since wednesday because of the holidays
horacio ruiz, a la prensa editor, said sunday the paper would publish monday with stockpiled paper
government offices and most businesses and restaurants have been closed since wednesday afternoon
deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco, in a friday-dated letter to contra leader aristides sanchez, said it was ``extremely important to follow the outline of the cease-fire plan,'' referring to the talks that had been scheduled for wednesday
tinoco blamed the contras for the lack of progress during the technical meetings, saying the rebel delegation arrived late on the first day and insisted on ending the talks promptly at 5 p.m. on the second day
the two sides planned to hold another round of technical negotiations starting tuesday at sapoa, 90 miles south of the capital on the border with costa rica
under the truce plan, contra combatants are to move into designated zones during the first two weeks of april. there would be a second release of political prisoners after it was verified the rebels were in the zones

