am-political briefs, a0746:
_ new york congressman urging cuomo to run for president
_ wisconsin delegation predicts bush will do better than expected
voters on tuesday will choose a fresh face to occupy the mayor's office in a closely contested race that marks the end of incumbent mayor henry maier's reign of nearly three decades
maier has held his office since 1960, longer than any other big-city mayor in the country. the 70-year-old maier cited his age as reason for not running for another term
the two contenders vying for his job are state sen. john norquist, 38, and former acting gov. martin schreiber, 48. the race is non-partisan; both contenders have run for other offices in the past as democrats
when the campaign began, polls put norquist well behind. but his support grew, and he finished 4 percentage points behind schreiber in the february primary. recent polls put the race a dead heat
during maier's tenure, the city enjoyed a downtown renaissance but suffered from lingering racial divisions, and his performance received mixed reviews from the two candidates
the good thing about him is that he's strong and he makes decisions and deep down inside he cares deeply about the city,'' norquist said. ``(but) he had trouble dealing with his enemies, dealing with his critics. i think henry would take criticism too much as a personal criticism.''
schreiber, meanwhile, said maier ``has established an excellent foundation on which we can build.''
both candidates praised the downtown revitalization, but they noted more attention should go toward the inner-city neighborhoods, which hold the potentially key black vote. about one-fourth of the city's 600,000 residents are black
schreiber won the endorsement of a black convention organized by the third-place finisher in the mayoral primary, lee holloway. norquist boycotted the event, objecting to a $20 admission fee charged by holloway to help retire his campaign debt
but norquist may be able to draw on support from key members of the black community, including alderman michael mcgee and state sen. gary george
the biggest single economic problem that we have is the high black unemployment rate,'' norquist said. the federal bureau of labor statistics reported in 1985 that black unemployment in the milwaukee metropolitan area was about 28 percent
the race between schreiber and norquist has centered as much on their personalities as it has on the issues, where the two candidates often sound similar
schreiber cultivated an image of being a likable candidate who, as mayor, would bring together different factions to address the city's problems and promote harmony
but he is criticized for trying to please too many people and making promises on issues without having all the facts
for example, schreiber won the endorsement of the primary's fourth-place finisher, donna horowitz richards, when he announced support of her proposed development programs for neighborhoods
but he then was unable to answer certain questions about the plan, and afterward he backed off his position, saying he would promise to study the ideas
i am not a hotshot and i don't have all the answers,'' schreiber said. ``all of my strengths and all of my successes have been brought about by getting people around the table and talking about an issue and then developing a plan.''
norquist portrayed himself as a take-charge candidate who offers detailed programs. but he has been criticized for being too strident, which schreiber insists proves his opponent's ``instability.''
while norquist says he has tried to tone down emotions, he adds: ``a mayor ought to be able to get angry, especially when it's something that affects the city.''
schreiber was elected lieutenant governor 1970 after eight years in the state senate. he became acting governor in 1977 when gov. patrick lucey resigned to become ambassador to mexico. but the following year, schreiber lost the general election for a full term as governor to his republican challenger
norquist, at 6-foot-7 nearly a foot taller than schreiber, served in the state assembly from 1974 to 1982, when he was elected to the senate. iran</head> iraq denouncing u.n. pick up 4th pvs: the latest ... and edits to tighten</note>
iraqi troops killed 400 kurdish civilians who had been injured in a chemical-bomb attack and were trying to reach a hospital, a kurdish guerrilla leader said sunday
the report could not be independently confirmed. neither iraq nor iran, which backs the iraqi kurdish separatists, had immediate comment
iraq, meanwhile, said its warplanes raided two iranian refineries sunday but iran said the bombs hit residential areas, killing 10 civilians and wounding 50
in tehran, a senior official told reporters iran would respond to the renewed attacks on his nation's cities with ground offensives
kurdish guerrilla leader jalal talabani said the 400 civilians from the mountainous qara dagh district were wounded in an iraqi chemical raid
talabani, leader of the patriotic union of kurdistan, said the wounded were traveling to a hospital in the northeastern city of sulaymaniyah when they were taken prisoner by iraqi soldiers and killed on saturday
talabani is in london and made the accusation in a telephoned statement
kurdish separatists have been fighting the iraqi government for decades for an independent homeland
qara dagh is 20 miles west of lake darbandikhan, where iran claims iraqi chemical bombings march 16-17 killed 5,000 civilians and injured many more. a senior iraqi official on sunday repeated the claim that u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar is biased toward iran
akram al-witri, chief of the legal department at the foreign ministry, told a news conference, ``we have been patient but now we are fed up with perez de cuellar and other top u.n. officials who are appeasing iran for their self interest.''
last week iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz expressed ``bitterness and disappointment at the biased and ill-balanced nature'' of recent statements by perez de cuellar on the alleged use of chemical weapons by iraq
al-witri accused perez de cuellar of neglecting the fate of iraqi prisoners of war. ``our 45,000 pows in iran are subject to all kinds of physical and psychological torture and other methods of maltreatment and it is time'' that the united nations and international red cross investigate, he said
it was the first time iraq has said iran is holding 45,000 war prisoners
also sunday, an iranian military spokesman for the first time listed an overall casualty toll in just over a month of iraqi air and missile attacks on iranian cities _ 1,145 dead and 4,000 wounded. iraq has said hundreds of its civilians have been killed in similar raids
the latest attacks, which were among 140 warplane combat missions reported by the iraqi news agency during the day, signaled a rekindling of the ``war of the cities'' after a 2{-day break
iraq anounced its forces sank six iranian gunboats during the night as they attempted to approach an offshore oil platform in the northern persian gulf. iran denied the claim
the official iraqi news agency quoted a military communique as saying the strikes on iran's refineries near the cities of isfahan and tabriz were carried out at 2:40 p.m
that was about six hours after turkish prime minister turgut ozal left the iraqi capital. baghdad had ceased its attacks on iranian cities during ozal's visit and had announced it would not resume attacks for six hours after ozal left
in tehran, kamal kharrazi, head of the war information headquarters, told reporters that 10 people were killed in tabriz. iran's official islamic republic news agency (irna) said another 50 were wounded
the iranian agency said anti-aircraft batteries shot down one of the warplanes at isfahan ``seconds after the attack'' on the city
it said the pilot, talal ibrahim, no rank given, was taken prisoner by iranian forces. an iraqi military communique said an iraqi plane ``crashed inside enemy territory.''
asked whether iran would retaliate for sunday's raids, iranian deputy foreign minister mohammad javad larijani told reporters in tehran:
we will have plenty of surprises for them,'' but they would be mainly on the battlefield through ``punitive offensives.''
these offensives will stop them definitely, and they will pay a high price,'' he said
turkish sources said ozal, who arrived in ankara later sunday, had proposed that iran and iraq call a cease-fire in the ``war of the cities,'' which began feb. 29
ozal said in a departure statement that turkey is trying to help the united nations end the 7{-year-old war between iran and iraq
irna quoted a spokesman for the war information headquarters as denying iraq's claims that it trounced iran and its kurdish separatist allies in fighting last week in mountainous northeastern iraq
iraq said saturday that its forces killed thousands of iranians and overran kurdish guerrilla bases, scoring a major victory and recapturing tracts of iraqi soil
the iranian spokesman said iran was ``in full control'' of all the towns and strategic heights captured during an offensive that began in mid-march
a senior chinese envoy, meanwhile, arrived in saudi arabia carrying a message from president li xiannian to king fahd dealing with the iran-iraq war, the official saudi press agency reported
it said chinese vice foreign minister qi huaiyuan handed the written message to saudi foreign minister prince saud al-faisal. the contents were not disclosed
