iraqi troops seized 400 civilians who had been wounded by chemical weapons and were en route to a hospital, then massacred them at a military camp, a kurdish guerrilla leader said sunday
jalal talabani said the civilians from iraq's qara dagh district were wounded in a recent iraqi chemical-bomb attack. the predominantly kurdish district is in a mountainous border region that has been the scene of fierce fighting
talabani, leader of the patriotic union of kurdistan, said the wounded were traveling to a hospital in the northeastern city of sulaymaniyah when they were taken prisoner by iraqi soldiers
they were forced to go to to the nearby tanjero military camp where they were all killed on saturday, he said
talabani, who is in london and made the accusation in a telephoned statement, said he did not know what weapons were used to kill the prisoners
the report could not be independently confirmed. neither iraq nor iran, which backs the iraqi kurdish separatists, had an immediate comment
talabani also said there were no iranian troops in the qara dagh region, and it was controlled by kurdish separatists
qara dagh is about 20 miles west of lake darbandikhan, where iranian revolutionary guards have seized iraqi territory in an offensive that began in mid-march
kurdish separatists have repeatedly claimed the iraqi government is waging a campaign of genocide against the kurds
iraq, at war with iran since september 1980, has come under international criticism for using chemical weapons in the fighting
iran claims iraqi chemical bombings march 16-17 in the lake darbandikhan area killed 5,000 civilians and injured many more
the united nations has said it will send a team of experts to investigate the reported use of chemical weapons, outlawed under a 1925 geneva agreement
a pet pig named chop chop has become the animal kingdom's surfing champion, doing a porcine version of a ``hang ten'' as he rode through the waves with his owner and garnering a perfect score
a dozen surfers paired up with dogs, geese and even fish in an aquarium saturday at the ``wet pet'' exhibition at the rell sunn menehune surfing championships. riding tandem on longboards, human and pet surfers competed before a crowd of 2,000 at makaha beach on oahu
professional surfer and lifeguard brian keaulana, 26, and 3-month-old chop chop came in first with their perfect score
it was a great ride,'' keaulana said. ``i slapped the pig in the behind and it went to the nose
he did kind of a hang ten, but pigs have cloven hoofs, so i guess it was more like a hang four,'' keaulana said. ``he liked it a lot. he was jumping around and going crazy.''
the ``wet pet'' exhibition is part of the rell sunn menehune, a surfing competition for children 15 and under
keaulana doubts he and chop chop will return to defend their title in 1989
he'll probably be 300 pounds next year,'' keaulana said. ``it'll be tough to get him on the board.''
keaulana won a trophy and chop chop won a reprieve from becoming the main course at a luau
