mormon church leaders praised jesus christ as the resurrected son of god to close the faith's 158th annual general conference sunday with an easter theme reaffirming fundamental church doctrine
the gathering closed with a sermon written by president ezra taft benson telling listeners to demonstrate their love for god by obeying his laws
i pray that we will be obedient to god, learn his will and do it, and above all, that we will keep the first and great commandment _ to love the lord with all our heart, soul, mind and strength,'' said the sermon, which was read by gordon b. hinckley, a counselor in the church's ruling first presidency
benson's sermon said mormons should consider whether they are adhering to the church's principles, such as participating in missionary work, daily scripture reading, and building family unity with weekly activities
it also stressed the longstanding admonition that church members prepare for possible emergencies by keeping on hand enough food, clothing and other essential supplies to last one year
a church official said the 88-year-old benson asked hinckley to read the sermon for him because he was tired
earlier, hinckley delivered his own homily saying christ submitted to crucifixion to make the resurrection of all men and women possible through his own death. mormon doctrine holds that mankind will be resurrected in perfect, immortal physical bodies before the final judgment
of all the victories of human history, none is so great, none so universal in its effect, none so everlasting in its consequences, as the victory of the crucified lord who came forth in the resurrection that first easter morning,'' hinckley said
joseph b. wirthlin, a member of the twelve, a group of clergy that assist the first presidency, urged mormons to follow christ by emulating his honesty, which he said includes paying employees a fair wage, filing accurate tax returns and not padding expense accounts
the leaders spoke as part of a series of 12 sermons capping the two-day conference, in which speakers stressed the church's basic beliefs about christ's resurrection
critics have accused mormons of exalting joseph smith, who believers say found the church in 1820 after god and jesus appeared to him, to a level equal to or surpassing jesus. but the speakers gave no indication that their remarks were in response to such criticism
the conference, attended by more than 6,000 church members, also was told saturday that the church attracted a record 227,284 converts during 1987, bringing total membership to 6.5 million
vietnam is scheduled to make its largest release of what are believed to be remains of u.s. military personnel missing in action in the vietnam war that ended with a communist victory in 1975
a u.s. military team is to receive the 27 sets of remains on wednesday at hanoi's noi bai airport and fly them to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu for analysis
it would be the fourth turnover since retired gen. john w. vessey, acting as president reagan's special emissary, reached an agreement in hanoi, the vietnamese capital, last august that ended months of deadlocked negotiatons on the issue
positive identifications of the 27 sets of remains would mean substantial progress because hanoi has returned only 152 confirmed sets since the war
the two nations often have quarreled over accounting for the 1,767 americans who remain listed as missing in action in vietnam
the largest previous transfer of remains was on aug. 14, 1985. it involved 26 sets, and at least 24 have been identified as american remains
a u.s. official closely involved in the issue said recently that while progress since the vessey agreement had not been as rapid as washington had hoped, hanoi has been much more responsive to u.s. requests to investigate reports involving mias
the vietnamese have been discussing the issue with an increasing number of congressmen and other american visitors, many of whom return to urge increased official contacts with hanoi
in march, the vietnamese met with john leboutillier, a former congressman who now heads a private lobbying group that insists there are still americans being held prisoners in vietnam
the mia issue also is on the agendas of u.s. sens. larry pressler, r-s.d., and g.v. sonny montgomery, d-mo., who are separately visiting hanoi this week
the u.s. official said the vietnamese have indicated they did not believe washington was implementing humanitarian provisions of the vessey agreement. he said the vietnamese complained that the united states has only sent exploratory medical teams and encouraged private u.s. agencies to aid vietnam's disabled war veterans and other humanitarian cases
they're not making a secret that they prefer direct government-to-government aid,'' said the official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity
the united states and vietnam do not have diplomatic relations
afghan president najib on sunday declared the first day of general elections a national holiday, the government's radio station reported
the elections, scheduled to begin tuesday, come at a time when negotiations are under way in switzerland on the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet military personnel in afghanistan
as proposed by the election commission, the 5th of april will be a national holiday on the occasion of the elections for the national assembly,'' radio kabul quoted najib as saying in a decree
one-fourth of the 62 senate and 229 house of deputies seats are to be set aside for rebel candidates, even if they do not participate. the elections are to run until april 14
most members of the election commission organizing the balloting are from the marxist government
the guerrillas have refused any power-sharing with the communists and have vowed to fight until they overthrow the government
radio kabul's broadcast of najib's statement was monitored in islamabad
leftists in the armed foreces seized power in a coup in april 1978. soviet troops intervened in december 1979 to help the faltering government battle the guerrillas
the united states, soviet union, afghanistan and pakistan have been involved for months in u.n.-sponsored efforts to bring about a withdrawal of the soviet troops and a peaceful settlement in the war
talks in geneva recessed for the easter holiday and are to resume monday
a company that advertised that it could help businesses secure loans is facing an fbi investigation and lawsuits from unhappy ex-clients who paid high fees but never received financing, according to a report published sunday
the boston sunday globe reported that since its founding in 1986, first boston charter corp. has collected between $2 million and $50 million from clients seeking loans. but dozens of clients interviewed by the newspaper reported that they didn't get any loans and were unable to recover their fees
three ex-clients have sued fbc in u.s. district court in boston, and a federal grand jury in las vegas has indicted the executives of several companies with which fbc works. an fbi spokesman said the agency has launched an investigation of first boston charter and several of the companies it deals with
the company is unrelated to the new york-based securities firm, first boston corp
fbc president marc w. anderson refused to be interviewed, the globe said. his associate, paul j. gilbert, also refused comment and referred questions to william m. codinha, the boston lawyer representing the company
codinha told the globe that after consulting his clients, he decided it was ``not in their interest'' to talk
according to the globe, fbc works with numerous other companies in arranging loans and loan guarantees. the various companies involved claim to be independent of each other, the globe said, but in fact are linked in some way
george h. jones jr., 56, of allentown, pa., told the globe he went to fbc when he and a partner were looking for a $500,000 loan to set up a charter bus company and saw a newspaper advertisement for fbc
he told the globe that fbc officials told him that fbc did not make loans, but would get him a loan guarantee _ a promise that money he borrowed would be repaid even if the bus company failed. fbc also told him that a second company would issue the guarantee
jones said that while the second company did not make the actual loan, it would direct him to a third company that would come up with the money
jones told the newspaper that fbc executives warned him that there would be risks in the deal
however, jones said, by the beginning of 1987, he had paid fbc a $20,000 fee, a $3,500 fee to a company called first fidelity finance for a ``character and credit investigation'' and was making $1,000 monthly fee payments to another company in on the deal, euro-shares, based in spain
last august, jones said, he lost his bus company and he eventually had to sell his car and put his house on the market because of indebtedness
edward showalter, an ohio manufacturer who sought a $1 million loan through a series of companies that involved fbc's anderson to produce a line of clothing featuring cartoon characters, told the newspaper a story similar to jones'. showalter paid several companies fees totaling $42,500 but never received the $1 million loan he was seeking, according to the globe
in a suit filed here, businessman richard p. johnson of stuart, fla., contends he and a client of his paid fees totaling $70,000 to fbc for help in securing $35 million in loans, but never received any financing
one of several european companies to which fbc clients are referred, euro-kredit, n.a., is owned by alan copeland, who is under indictment in las vegas for fraud. copeland's real name is bruce cooper and he is a convicted bank robber and con man, the newspaper reported
five other people were also indicted last fall _ two copeland colleagues and three executives of other companies affiliated with first boston, the newspaper said. the various companies are accused of working together to defraud clients, splitting the large fees but failing to provide loans
the newspaper said first boston charter claimed to have growing numbers of satisified customers, but declined to name any of them
according to the globe, records in ohio and california show that anderson changed his name shortly before arriving in boston to set up first boston charter in mid-1986. before the change, his name was william marc knasel, the globe said
at least three people were wounded sunday in a shooting at a funeral at a church, hospital officials said
details of the shooting at mountain home baptist church were sketchy and the number of victims was not immediately known. the shooting occurred shortly before 3 p.m., when the funeral of effie collins justice was scheduled
andrea rainey, 40, was taken to margaret pardee hospital in hendersonville where she began undergoing surgery at 5:30 p.m. for a bullet wound, officials said
wendy johnston, 11, was in good condition and was being transported to memorial mission hospital in asheville, along with her mother, shelia johnston, 30. mrs. johnston was in critical condition and the extent of her injuries was not known
a 3-year-old boy visiting his grandfather's grave with his parents was fatally crushed when a tombstone fell on him, police said
christopher rigsby was pronounced dead on arrival at union memorial hospital on saturday after suffering severe head injuries, a police spokesman said
relatives were hammering a small wooden cross into the grandfather's grave as an easter decoration saturday morning when the headstone of an adjacent grave fell forward on top of christopher, crushing him, police said
joseph r. swift, the cemetery manager, said he called police after he was informed of the incident and then walked out of his office to see julia rigsby, 26, sitting in the back of a car holding her unconscious son in her lap
she wouldn't let anyone near the boy until an ambulance came,'' swift said
the granite headstone, which was about 3 feet tall by 2 feet wide, fell away from its foot-high base, swift said. the marker had been attached to the base with an epoxy seal
the boy's grandmother, roberta malantrucolo, told police she had stopped the boy from climbing on some tombstones earlier, swift said
the shipbuilders' union at the bath iron works has rejected a proposed three-year contract that both the company and union had hoped would usher in a new era of labor peace
however, saturday's vote did not signal authorization for a strike. the 5,500-member union and the company are expected to stick with the existing contract that expires aug. 14 and re-enter negotiations sometime this summer
biw had invited its unions to open contract talks early, in hopes of improving its competitiveness. it lost four of five navy cruiser contracts in february to rival ingalls shipbuilding of mississippi
the proposed contract, which offered three annual 2.5 percent wage increases and the phase-out of a two-tier pay system that gives less to new employees, was rejected by a margin of roughly 3 to 2, said ray ladd, president of local 6 of the industrial union of marine and shipbuilding workers of america
about 2,500 of the union's approximately 5,500 members participated in the voting
i feel it should have gone through, because i don't feel they're going to offer any more in august,'' ladd said
duane d. fitzgerald, biw's executive vice president, issued a statement saying management officials were ``disappointed with the result but believe the process was constructive and informative.''
we do not regret having made the effort,'' fitzgerald said
ladd blamed the rejection in part on members' desire for bigger pay hikes and a swifter end to the two-tier wage system. he said he understood rank-and-file sentiments but added, ``the company hasn't got any money. they opened the books and proved it.''
under the current contract, newer employees have been paid about $3 less an hour than veteran workers. the rejected company proposal would have phased out the two-tier system in april 1990
the proposed 2.5 percent wage increase would have amounted to 29 cents an hour more for first-class mechanics in the first two years of the contract and 30 cents an hour more the final year
members of local 7, a much smaller union representing 393 clerical and technical workers, overwhelmingly approved a new three-year contract a week ago
the shipyard, maine's largest private employer, reached its highest peacetime employment level last month, reporting 8,900 workers on its payroll
police and troops moved to tighten security along india's frontier with pakistan sunday and three more deaths were blamed on sikh extremists in northern punjab state that borders pakistan
prime minister rajiv gandhi on friday ordered increased border security to try to stem the delivery of weapons to the sikh separatists in punjab. india contends sikh militants are receiving arms smuggled from pakistan
sikh extremists killed at least 120 people in the week ending saturday, the highest one-week toll since separatists began a guerrilla war for their own homeland in 1982. many of the victims were hindus, but moderate sikhs also have been slain by the militants
patrols were stepped up along the indo-pakistan border in northern kashmir state, united news of india reported. punjab is south of kashmir and east of pakistan
police and paramilitary unit commanders are scheduled to meet monday in the sikh holy city of amritsar to discuss increased security in punjab
several indian newspapers reported sunday that the government was considering the construction of fences along parts of the indo-pakistan border as well as increased patrols
united news of india said two people, who it did not identify, were shot to death in gurdaspur district in separate attacks late saturday and sunday. a village leader was killed in amritsar district saturday night, the news agency said. he was identified as nirmal singh, a sikh
the latest killings raised to at least 648 the number of deaths blamed on sikh extremists in punjab this year. in 1987, about 1,000 people were slain in violence related to the separatists' campaign
punjab gov. s.s. ray on sunday visited three villages where 28 people were shot to death by sikh militants last week. he pledged government assistance to the survivors
eighteen of the victims were hindus living in a hamlet near the village of pangota, 24 miles north of amritsar
sikhs, whose religion is an offshoot of hinduism and islam, make up only 2 percent of india's 800 million population, but they are a majority in punjab
more than five months after jessica mcclure's dramatic rescue from a narrow well gripped the nation, the child and her family continue to grapple with the ups and downs of their celebrity status
the texas rangers expect their opening-day game monday to be packed as jessica tosses out the first ball of the season at arlington stadium
that was hardly the mcclures' only offer
later, i got a call from the houston astros,'' said former state sen. pete snelson of midland, the family's publicist. he said he turned down the astros' request for jessica because the family didn't have time for their tuesday opener
last week, jessica and her mother, reba ``cissy'' mcclure, traveled to lancaster in north central texas to help fund-raising efforts for a 5-year-old boy who faces heart and lung transplants
but not all the attention leveled at the family has been flattering
the mcclures bought a new three-bedroom tract house in the modest suburb of greenwood. mrs. mcclure, who turned 19 last week, stays home with jessica while her 18-year-old husband works at a new job selling sporting goods at a local store
but when oprah winfrey brought her television talk show to midland and sent a limousine to pick up the mcclures, rumors spread that the couple was living in a large home in an exclusive neighborhood
that's when the rumors started flying,'' said m.l. blevins, accountant for the mcclures. he dismissed the talk, estimating the value of the mcclures' new home at between $30,000 and $40,000
snelson said the mcclures' lifestyle has remained relatively spartan, despite large sums of money placed into a trust fund and forwarded in other donations
but the family's fame remains strong and the notoriety hasn't been all bad for a town that had been hit hard by the slump in oil and gas prices
i got a letter the other day _ a registered letter _ addressed to `jessica's mayor,''' said carroll thomas, midland mayor
thomas recently formed a committee to choose the best movie deal about the well rescue and break an impasse between two associations of rescuers pursuing separate agreements
initially, he said, the rescue ``did a lot to take our minds off the oil business problems. it gave us a chance to think about the fact that there are things just as important (as), if not more important than, money.'' with jackson comment; inserts 2 grafs after 28th graf pvs, under questioning, with later comment from kirk spokeswoman</note>
the presidential candidates took their politicking to easter church services on sunday as they battled for victory in this week's campaign double feature _ the colorado caucuses and wisconsin primary
republican pat robertson, whose candidacy is all but derailed by vice president george bush's march to the nomination, said he has a mandate from god and won't stop until he is president of the united states
saying he would run again in 1992, robertson told about 3,000 people at denver's happy church that ``i am not going to quit ... that is his plan for me and for this nation.''
but with bush's nomination virtually assured, the 1988 focus is now on the democrats
sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, who has staked hopes of reviving his trailing campaign with a good showing in wisconsin on tuesday, picked up the endorsement this weekend of the milwaukee journal
the newspaper cited gore's ``impressive record'' in arms control, military reform and environmental protection, cand called him ``one of congress' best informed members on the future of science and technology.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who shares frontrunner status with jesse jackson, was asked by reporters outside a milwaukee church if he shared the view of some democrats that jackson is not electable because he his black and too liberal
i don't think there is any way of knowing,'' dukakis said
democratic party chairman paul kirk also sidestepped that question sunday when interviewed on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley'' program
we haven't nominated anyone yet,'' he said. ``the democratic party will do its best to nominate, i hope, the most electable candidate in order to win in november.''
jackson on sunday showed no concern about reports of consternation among democrats over his recent momentum
speaking to overflow crowds at two denver churches, he continued to hammer home the themes that have brought a burgeoning response to his campaign
at the first baptist church, where 1,500 people jammed inside and at least as many listened to him on loudspeakers outside, jackson said:
i sense as i travel around the nation something is going on. there are several thousand people outdoors _ something is going on
from aspen to alabama _ something is going on ... hope has been unleased.''
later, in a predominantly hispanic neighborhood, people lined the street for a block to see jackson arrive at our lady of guadalupe catholic church
jackson's success in the primaries and caucuses _ including a victory over dukakis in the virgin islands on saturday _ has created a sticky issue for democrats bent on picking a nominee who can secure the white house
his campaign chairman, california assembly speaker willie brown said sunday that the margin of jackson's successes has surprised even him. but he said that even if jackson gets the most delegates by the end of the primary season, that doesn't mean he should get the nomination
you can have a plurality of the delegates and still not be able to reach the 2,082 required to secure the nomination,'' brown said on ``this week with david brinkley.''
i only believe he's entitled to the nomination if we succeed in producing the appropriate number of delgates that george mcgovern got, that fritz mondale got, or that jimmy carter got,'' brown said
but brown also raised the possibility of the jackson forces instigating a rules fight at the convention this summer if the delegate race does not play out as they think it fairly should
jackson himself downplayed the possibility it would come to that
we're certainly going to stand for fairness, but i hope it won't come to a fight. i think that most demcrats are going to stand for that which is fair and that which is right,'' he said as he campaigned in colorado
it appears unlikely any democrat will have enough delegates in hand to secure the nomination at the end of the primary season in june. the nomination thus will lie in the hands of the so-called super delegates, who are automatically delegates by virtue of their position as party leaders or elected officials
dukakis so far has won 653.5 delegates to jackson's 646.5 and gore's 381.8, according to the associated press tally
democratic leader kirk on sunday appeared to moderate his suggestion that his party should rally behind whoever is the frontrunner at the end of the primary season
kirk said that a candidate who emerges with the most delegates, but shy of the needed 2,082, should not automatically get the party's nod
that's not what the rules say. the rules say that the person who attains a majority of delegates will be the party's nominee,'' he said
he said that when he earlier had talked about getting party leaders together to solidify support for a frontrunner, he meant that if anyone gained ``a very very substantial plurality of delegates and someone has the nomination within virtually within his grasp, that the party ought to sit down'' and talk about getting behind that person
under questioning, he refused to say what would consistute a substantial plurality
spokeswoman julie anbender later said kirk's views on the matter have not changed
kirk has not altered his position about rallying behind the clear-cut frontrunner. he continues to believe that at the end of the process, one of our candidates will clearly emerge from the pack and kirk will at that point encourage the party to rally behind its inevitable nominee,'' she said
brown noted that the jackson campaign is actively seeking out support among the superdelegates and the uncommitted delegates, particularly members of congress who represent districts where jackson has run strongly
as if the jackson forces would, as they did at the 1984 convention, challenge any rules on how delegates are selected should jackson fail to bring many uncommitted delegates on board, brown said
i think if the rules need to be challenged we will do so.''
jackson previously has said he has no plans to raise rules challenges at the summer convention in atlanta. but he has also said he expects the party to treat him fairly
a panamanian military vehicle on sunday tried to stop the car of u.s. ambassador arthur davis, the u.s. embassy reported and it called the ``serious.''
terence kneebone, an embassy spokesman, said davis was leaving the residence of the vatican's ambassador in a chauffeur-driven car when a military ``vehicle began following immediately, picking them up right outside the gate
it followed them down balboa avenue, then tried to stop them with lights and sirens. the ambassador's driver, in accordance with instructions, did not stop. the ambassador was driven to his residence, and the other vehicle followed all the way.''
we consider this serious,'' kneebone added. he said that would be the embassy's only characterization of the incident and referred further questions to the state department in washington
kneebone said davis had gone to call on the papal nuncio, monsignor jose sebastian laboa, to pay his respects on easter sunday. the spokesman noted that the papal ambassador is the dean of the diplomatic corps in panama
the distance between laboa's residence and the american ambassador's house is about two miles, and the route followed by davis' car took him along oceanfront balboa avenue
sunday's edition of the daily newspaper la republica, which is run by the military, carried a front-page picture of davis with a caption that said he did not venture from his residence unless he was ``armed to the teeth.''
the brief article accused the ambassador of ``exaggerating'' any possible threat to his personal security and said davis suffered from either ``a persecution complex'' or ``guilty conscience.''
the incident came only three days after the panamanian government said the defense forces, commanded by gen. manuel antonio noriega, would not do anything to provoke an excuse for a u.s. invasion. the united states has demanded that noriega, under federal indictment in florida on drug-trafficking charges, resign
in its statement the government said, ``aware of the overwhelming power threatening it, the republic of panama ... will not provide the foundation for fabrication of a charge of aggression that could pretent to justify the launching of acts of war.''
the last act of gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial begins monday with attorneys' final arguments, wrapping up a historical drama involving charges of obstruction of justice and misuse of state funds
if the arizona senate votes against him, mecham would become the seventh u.s. governor removed from office by impeachment. the vote could come as early as monday
it would take a two-thirds vote or 20 of the senators to convict mecham, who has only been in office a little more than a year. the body then could take a second vote and bar him from holding state office again
if he is acquitted, mecham would still face a recall election may 17. he also faces a criminal trial on felony charges associated with alleged concealment of a $350,000 campaign loan. that charge was included in the articles of impeachment but was thrown out by senators last week in a surprise vote
the first impeachment charge alleges that mecham, 63, obstructed justice by impeding an attorney general's investigation of an alleged death threat on a grand jury witness by one of mecham's staff members. the witness, a former mecham aide, had agreed to testify about mecham's campaign finances
in the second charge, he is accused of illegally lending public funds _ $80,000 from a protocol fund _ to his auto dealership
an underlying question is whether either of the charges, if sustained, constitutes ``high crimes, malfeasance and misdeameanors,'' the requirement for removing an elected official
the prosecution, in a trial memorandum, urged senators to convict mecham
the criminal acts and the acts of abuse of power, breach of public trust, neglect of duty and obstruction of justice demand that gov. mecham be removed from office,'' they said
defense lawyers said they would respond with written arguments monday. but after five weeks of testimony, the respective positions are clear
prosecutors say the first-term republican governor instructed the state's top lawman, ralph milstead, not to cooperate with an attorney general's investigation of the alleged death threat
mecham, who says he was politically ``at war'' with the attorney general, concedes he may have said something like that but insists he acted out of ignorance of the facts. mecham claims no one told him details of the alleged threat
a key issue is the credibility of several witnesses, the key ones being mecham and milstead
the second charge involves money. mecham says money raised by his inaugural committee to pay off his campaign debts always remained private money even after a law prevented its use for its original purpose. the prosecution says it became public money when it was placed in a protocol fund to pay for gifts to visiting dignitaries and events enhancing the image of arizona
undisputed is the fact that mecham loaned $80,000 from the fund to his car dealership, did not record the deed of trust and paid it back three months later with interest when another campaign finance scandal erupted over the $350,000 loan
prosecutors will say that mecham's loan was unethical and illegal. defense lawyers will say it was legal and for the good of the state. mecham has contended his only motive was to increase the fund by paying higher interest than it was getting at a bank, disputing the prosecution's contention that the dealership was in financial difficulty and needed the money
arguments were expected to take about two hours, with each side speaking a half hour on each charge
the procedure of the senators voting on each charge separately could be lengthy, whether it starts monday or tuesday. unlike jurors in a court trial, the 30 senators each get 15 minutes to explain their votes. graf pvs: ``during this lenten...</note>
a panamanian military vehicle tried to stop the chauffeur-driven limousine of u.s. ambassador arthur davis on sunday but the diplomat continued on to his residence, the u.s. embassy reported
it called the incident ``serious.''
the effort to stop the ambassador came after panamanians rich and poor attended church services observing a somber easter in the crisis over the refusal of gen. manuel antonio noriega to resign
noriega commands the 15,000-member defense forces and as the military strongman is the power behind the civilian government. he is under indictment by a federal grand jury in florida, and has rejected u.s. demands that he resign
terence kneebone, a u.s. embassy spokesman, said davis had visited the vatican ambassador and was leaving in his car when a military ``vehicle began following immediately, picking them up right outside the gate
it followed them down balboa avenue, then tried to stop them with lights and sirens. the ambassador's driver, in accordance with instructions, did not stop. the ambassador was driven to his residence, and the other vehicle followed all the way.''
we consider this serious,'' kneebone added. he said that would be the embassy's only characterization of the incident and referred any further questions to the state department in washington
kneebone said davis had gone to call on the papal nuncio, monsignor jose sebastian laboa, to pay his respects on easter sunday. the spokesman noted that the papal ambassador is the dean of the diplomatic corps in panama
the distance between laboa's residence and the american ambassador's home is about two miles
sunday's edition of the military-run newspaper la republica carried a front-page picture of davis with a caption that said he did not venture from his residence unless he was ``armed to the teeth.''
a brief article accused the ambassador of ``exaggerating'' any possible threat to his personal security and said he suffered from either ``a persecution complex'' or ``guilty conscience.''
the incident came only three days after the panamanian government said the defense forces would not do anything to provoke an excuse for a u.s. invasion
aware of the overwhelming power threatening it, the republic of panama ... will not provide the foundation for fabrication of a charge of aggression that could pretend to justify the launching of acts of war,'' the government said
the united states has more than 10,000 military personnel in panama under the panamanian-based u.s. southern command. the reagan administration said friday it would sent 1,300 additional soldiers and marines to panama this week to reinforce security for americans and u.s.facilities in the country
in a televised mass, monsignor marcos a. mcgrath, the roman catholic archbishop of panama city, said, ``this sunday of the resurrection of 1988 is particularly dramatic for us.''
during this lenten season, we have suffered strong divisions, tensions among the panamanian people,'' he said. ``we have suffered many privations
in these final days of holy week, half of panama has been fasting because it has no food, and the other half has been fasting in sympathy with them.''
the country's economy has foundered since march 4 when noriega closed banks to prevent a run on cash made scarce by u.s. sanctions. the economic chaos was aggravated by a two-week-old general strike that closed down an estimated 90 percent of the country's business and industry
protesters have taken to the streets, and noriega's troops have responded with force
the strike eased late last week, with some groceries and pharmacies opening, reportedly under government pressure. opposition leaders have not formally called off the strike and were to meet sunday and monday to discuss whether to continue it
at a mass at cristo rey church, the rev. xavier villanueva, an outspoken noriega foe, urged catholics to support a recent call by panama's nine bishops for the general's resignation
the congregation broke into applause and many waved white handkerchiefs, which have become a symbol of dissent in panama's crisis
in his easter homily, mcgrath spoke of the nation's ``social decomposition.'' he referred to ``the reality of disintegrating homes, the reality of a people increasingly losing confidence in their leaders, the reality of a community misinformed by the partisanizing and falsifying of the news.''
the crisis, which had been building for months, erupted in late february when then-president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega, who had been indicted in the united states on drug-trafficking charges. delvalle's move backfired when noriega dismissed him
the quest for votes in tuesday's wisconsin primary took democratic presidential candidate paul simon to the bunny trail at a local park sunday
the illinois senator was surrounded by young and old as he appeared at wingra park during the traditional easter egg hunt. one little boy presented simon with a colored egg
simon, shown in the latest polls to be trailing far behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson in the wisconsin race, urged the youngsters to tell their parents to vote, and told voting-age onlookers to be sure to cast ballots on tuesday
he said his experience and his proposals for helping the poor and providing long-term health care separate him from other democratic candidates
i share (jackson's) passion for the less fortunate,'' simon said. ``i offer not only passion, but the experience to do something about it.''
as for dukakis, simon said, ``we need something more than a good manager...i have the experience with national issues that, frankly, mike doesn't have.''
