a town marshal who said he'd been kidnapped by burglars faked his highly publicized disappearance last week, a mississippi highway patrol investigator said
there was an attempted burglary at a local convenience store, but marshal gary stokes _ the town's only full-time policeman _ fabricated the tale of his abduction, state patrol investigator larry rickels said saturday
rickels said he had not uncovered a motive for the phony abduction
stokes could not be reached for comment sunday because his telephone was busy. his stepmother, mary stokes, said she was surprised by the investigator's finding, but didn't feel residents would be angry at her stepson because most were just glad he had returned unharmed
stokes, 35, disappeared about 12:55 a.m. thursday after calling for back-up units while investigating an attempted burglary in this northeastern mississippi town of 860 residents
police arriving at the store found his car with the engine still running, the lights on and his radio microphone hanging outside the door. his revolver and billfold were found nearby
stokes reappeared friday morning after claiming to have escaped from his captors
i knew i was done for anyway and i had nothing to lose,'' stokes said at the time. ``when they let me out of the trunk, i hit the ground running and i didn't look back.''
he told reporters that he was ``still nervous and kind of shook up. they had said several times they were going to kill me, and i believed them.''
rickels, however, said stokes apparently spent the night in the woods or an abandoned house in union county before turning up friday
in addition, the attempted burglary actually occurred thursday afternoon, much earlier than the alleged abduction, rickels said
