troops raided the seaside vacation house of opposition sen. juan ponce enrile on sunday but failed to find the leader of an august coup attempt who fled his prison ship, the military said
a manila paper, meanwhile, reported that nine other officers believed to be involved in past coup attempts had fled a detention center on saturday. the report could not be confirmed
the raid on enrile's house in batangas province, southwest of manila, was part of as nationwide search for former lt. col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan, leader of the aug. 28 coup attempt that nearly toppled the aquino government, said military officials
honasan, 39, escaped from a prison ship before dawn saturday with 14 elite navy personnel who were supposed to be guarding him. he had been confined there since his arrest dec. 9 for the attempted coup that left at least 53 people dead and hundreds wounded
president corazon aquino, who had refused to grant amnesty to honasan, warned soldiers and civilians not to aid the charismatic former colonel, who is popular among many in the 160,000-member armed forces
honasan served as chief of security at the defense ministry when enrile was defense chief. enrile told reporters sunday he had not heard from honasan since the escape
i'm beginning to sense that they treat me as an enemy,'' said enrile, who was fired in november 1986, after an alleged coup attempt by his followers. ``why don't they say it openly and publicly?''
chief of staff gen. renato de villa ordered a nationwide alert in the wake of honasan's escape and warned that leftist and rightist extremists may try to exploit the confusion created by the former colonel's dramatic flight
trucks blocked all entrances to military garrisons in the capital, and troops refused to allow reporters and other civilians to enter the compounds
police set up checkpoints on the outskirts of manila and placed homes of honasan's friends and associates under surveillance. extra troops were deployed around the presidential palace
de villa also ordered troops on alert in central and southern philippine islands in case disgruntled officers and politicians try to exploit the volatile situation in manila and stage attacks against government installations
the philippine daily inquirer reported monday that nine other soldiers held in connection with coup attempts last august and in january 1987 had fled the detention center at manila's villamor air base early saturday. the report could not be immediately confirmed
the newspaper quoted an unidentified air force officer as confirming the escape. the newspaper said the villamor incident strengthened speculation that honasan's escape was part of a broad conspiracy within the armed forces
manila newspapers also reported leaflets were circulating in military camps calling for the overthrow of the government. the leaflets allegedly were from honasan's reform the armed forces movement, the papers said
meanwhile, investigators said honasan and the others apparently fled the prison ship aboard rubber dinghies and came ashore near the folk arts center, a few hundred meters from the headquarters of the philippine navy
they then boarded seven cars which had been waiting for them, investigators said
the philippine daily globe reported monday that honasan left behind a note when he fled the ship saying he was escaping because ``the struggle for a better afp (armed forces of the philippines) must go on.''
honasan played a key role in the feb. 22, 1986, civilian-military uprising that toppled president ferdinand marcos and brought mrs. aquino to power. but he later accused mrs. aquino of weak and inept leadership in the face of the communist insurgency
lawyers may be close to a settlement that will compensate millions of people who bought kodak instant cameras but now can't get film, according to a published report
the chicago tribune, in its monday editions, said a settlement in cook county circuit court is expected in the next few weeks
serious negotiations are under way,'' william j. campbell jr., an attorney for eastman kodak co., told the tribune. he refused to comment further
a class-action lawsuit was brought against kodak more than two years ago on behalf of consumers who purchased instant cameras from 1976 through 1985, but who haven't been able to get film for the last three years because polaroid corp. sued kodak for patent infringement
william harte, attorney for the plaintiffs, said 16.5 million people bought the cameras, and about 4 million of those have been identified
the patent infringement suit brought by polaroid in federal court in boston led to a permanent injunction on sept. 13, 1985, that barred kodak from continuing to sell the instant cameras and film
harte's lawsuit, filed in circuit court on jan. 21, 1986, accuses kodak of failing to tell consumers that film might become unavailable. polaroid sued kodak shortly after it began marketing the instant camera in 1976
cook county circuit judge thomas rakowski had barred kodak from negotiating individual settlements with individual plaintiffs
